{"title_page": "Donald Liebenberg", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Donald Liebenberg\n| birth_date        = {{birth based on age as of date\u2009|85|2017|August|21|mos=1}}<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite news |last1=Koren |first1=Marina |title=The King of Totality |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/08/solar-eclipse-totality/537441/ |accessdate=24 September 2018 |work=The Atlantic |date=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       = \n| other_names       = \n| pronounce         = \n| residence         = [[Salem, South Carolina]]\n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = Astronomy\n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = University of Wisconsin\n| thesis_title      = <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url        = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year       = <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor  = <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| workplaces        = [[Clemson University]] (current)<br>[[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] (former)\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Having witnessed 27 total solar eclipses\n| spouse            = Norma Liebenberg\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n'''Donald Liebenberg''' is an American astronomer and adjunct professor in the department of physics and astronomy at [[Clemson University]].\n\nAn avowed [[eclipse chasing|eclipse chaser]], he best is known for having traveled around the world to see 27 total solar eclipses since 1954.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /><ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite news |last1=Greenfieldboyce |first1=Nell |title=Go See It, Eclipse Chasers Urge. 'Your First Time Is Always Special' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/08/08/539553696/go-see-it-eclipse-chasers-urge-your-first-time-is-always-special |accessdate=24 September 2018 |agency=NPR |date=8 August 2017}}</ref> He is also regarded as having spent more time in [[Solar eclipse#Terminology for central eclipse|totality]], the darkest area within the moon's [[umbra]] during a total [[solar eclipse]], than anyone else alive.<ref name=\"NPR\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Meet The Man About To Witness His 27th Total Solar Eclipse |url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/newsy/meet-the-man-about-to-witness-his-27th-total-solar-eclipse |accessdate=24 September 2018 |author-last1=Stephenson |author-first1=Lauren |author-last2=Seales |author-first2=Chance |agency=Newsy |publisher=ABC Action News WFTS |date=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nLiebenberg attended the [[University of Wisconsin]] as a physics major in the early 1950s.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /> He holds three degrees, including a PhD, from his alma mater.<ref name=\"Greenville\" />\n\n== Career and eclipses ==\nLiebenberg witnessed his first total solar eclipse on [[Solar eclipse of June 30, 1954|June 30, 1954]], in [[Mellen, Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"Greenville\">{{cite news |last1=LaFleur |first1=Elizabeth |title=Watch the eclipse and be 'amazed' like this guy who's seen 26 of them |url=https://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/news/local/2017/04/26/watch-eclipse-and-amazed-like-guy-whos-seen-26-them/100923904/ |accessdate=24 September 2018 |agency=Greenville News |date=27 April 2017}}</ref> Since then, he has traveled around the world to see solar eclipses, witnessing a total of 27 total solar eclipses. He observed his 27th, the [[solar eclipse of August 21, 2017]], from his driveway; by coincidence, his house in [[Salem, South Carolina]], was located in the path of totality.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /><ref name=\"Greenville\" /><ref name=\"Courier\" /><ref name=\"ClemNews2\">{{cite news |title=Liebenberg\u2019s research shines more light on coronal emissions during total solar eclipses |url=https://newsstand.clemson.edu/liebenbergs-research-shines-more-light-on-coronal-emissions-during-total-solar-eclipses/ |accessdate=8 July 2019 |website=Clemson Newsstand|date=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis primary motivation for pursuing solar eclipses has been to study the sun's [[solar corona|corona]].<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /> To this end, he wrote a proposal and obtained a grant from the [[National Science Foundation]] in 1954.<ref name=\"Greenville\" /> He later worked for the [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] carrying out research into the temperature and energy input of the corona.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /><ref name=\"Greenville\" /> In 1973, Liebenberg successfully petitioned French officials to commission an early [[Concorde]] supersonic aircraft for use in observing the [[solar eclipse of June 30, 1973]].<ref name=\"Courier\" /> Flying on the Concorde, a group of scientists from Los Alamos and the Paris Observarory, including Liebenberg, remained in the path of totality for 74 minutes while conducting various scientific measurements of the corona.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /><ref name=\"NPR\" /><ref name=\"Greenville\" /><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://permalink.lanl.gov/object/tr?what=info:lanl-repo/lareport/LA-UR-82-5105|title=In Flight: The Story of Los Alamos Eclipse Missions|first=Barb|last=Mulkin|journal=Los Alamos Science|accessdate=October 21, 2018}}</ref> For comparison, the theoretical maximum duration for totality during the third millennium for any stationary point or observer on the Earth's surface is approximately seven and a half minutes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meeus |first1=J |title=The maximum possible duration of a total solar eclipse |journal=Journal of the British Astronomical Association |volume=113 |page=344 (Table 1)|url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/2003JBAA..113..343M |accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe has worked as an adjunct professor in Clemson's department of physics and astronomy since 1996.<ref name=\"ClemNews\">{{cite web |last1=Melvin |first1=Jim |title=26 AND COUNTING / The Liebenberg Chronicles / Eclipse 9 / Part 2 of Concorde flight |url=http://newsstand.clemson.edu/26-and-counting-the-liebenberg-eclipse-chronicles-part-9/ |website=The Newsstand \u2013 Clemson University |accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nLiebenberg and his wife Norma<ref name=\"Courier\">{{cite news |last1=Borenstein |first1=Seth |title=Chasing eclipses across the globe is a way of life for some |url=https://www.postandcourier.com/solar_eclipse/chasing-eclipses-across-the-globe-is-a-way-of-life/article_aa94504e-83ba-11e7-8f31-6f0773d14e8e.html |accessdate=24 September 2018 |agency=The Post and Courier |date=17 August 2017}}</ref> reside in [[Salem, South Carolina]].<ref name=\"Atlantic\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.org/details/CSPAN2_20170818_041800_Interview_with_Donald_Liebenberg_on_the_Solar_Eclipse/start/0/end/60 Donald Liebenberg interview with CSPAN2]\n* [https://blogs.clemson.edu/eclipse/2017/06/25/26-and-counting-the-liebenberg-eclipse-chronicles-part-9/ Blog postings] where Liebenberg further discusses his experiences witnessing and researching solar eclipses\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liebenberg, Donald}}\n[[Category:Clemson University faculty]]\n[[Category:Los Alamos National Laboratory personnel]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1930s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Oconee County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin&ndash;Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:American astronomers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Donald Liebenberg\n| birth_date        = {{birth based on age as of date\u2009|85|2017|August|21|mos=1}}<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite news |last1=Koren |first1=Marina |title=The King of Totality |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/08/solar-eclipse-totality/537441/ |accessdate=24 September 2018 |work=The Atlantic |date=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       = \n| other_names       = \n| pronounce         = \n| residence         = [[Salem, South Carolina]]\n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = Astronomy\n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = University of Wisconsin\n| thesis_title      = <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url        = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year       = <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor  = <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| workplaces        = [[Clemson University]] (current)<br>[[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] (former)\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = Having witnessed 27 total solar eclipses\n| spouse            = Norma Liebenberg\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n'''Donald Liebenberg''' is an American astronomer and adjunct professor in the department of physics and astronomy at [[Clemson University]].\n\nAn avowed [[eclipse chasing|eclipse chaser]], he best is known for having traveled around the world to see 27 total solar eclipses since 1954.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /><ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite news |last1=Greenfieldboyce |first1=Nell |title=Go See It, Eclipse Chasers Urge. 'Your First Time Is Always Special' |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/08/08/539553696/go-see-it-eclipse-chasers-urge-your-first-time-is-always-special |accessdate=24 September 2018 |agency=NPR |date=8 August 2017}}</ref> He is also regarded as having spent more time in [[Solar eclipse#Terminology for central eclipse|totality]], the darkest area within the moon's [[umbra]] during a total [[solar eclipse]], than anyone else alive.<ref name=\"NPR\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Meet The Man About To Witness His 27th Total Solar Eclipse |url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/newsy/meet-the-man-about-to-witness-his-27th-total-solar-eclipse |accessdate=24 September 2018 |author-last1=Stephenson |author-first1=Lauren |author-last2=Seales |author-first2=Chance |agency=Newsy |publisher=ABC Action News WFTS |date=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nLiebenberg attended the [[University of Wisconsin]] as a physics major in the early 1950s.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /> He holds three degrees, including a PhD, from his alma mater.<ref name=\"Greenville\" />\n\n== Career and eclipses ==\nLiebenberg witnessed his first total solar eclipse on [[Solar eclipse of June 30, 1954|June 30, 1954]], in [[Mellen, Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"Greenville\">{{cite news |last1=LaFleur |first1=Elizabeth |title=Watch the eclipse and be 'amazed' like this guy who's seen 26 of them |url=https://www.greenvilleonline.com/story/news/local/2017/04/26/watch-eclipse-and-amazed-like-guy-whos-seen-26-them/100923904/ |accessdate=24 September 2018 |agency=Greenville News |date=27 April 2017}}</ref> Since then, he has traveled around the world to see solar eclipses, witnessing a total of 27 total solar eclipses. He observed his 27th, the [[solar eclipse of August 21, 2017]], from his driveway; by coincidence, his house in [[Salem, South Carolina]], was located in the path of totality.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /><ref name=\"Greenville\" /><ref name=\"Courier\" /><ref name=\"ClemNews2\">{{cite news |title=Liebenberg\u2019s research shines more light on coronal emissions during total solar eclipses |url=https://newsstand.clemson.edu/liebenbergs-research-shines-more-light-on-coronal-emissions-during-total-solar-eclipses/ |accessdate=8 July 2019 |website=Clemson Newsstand|date=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis primary motivation for pursuing solar eclipses has been to study the sun's [[corona]].<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /> To this end, he wrote a proposal and obtained a grant from the [[National Science Foundation]] in 1954.<ref name=\"Greenville\" /> He later worked for the [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] carrying out research into the temperature and energy input of the corona.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /><ref name=\"Greenville\" /> In 1973, Liebenberg successfully petitioned French officials to commission an early [[Concorde]] supersonic aircraft for use in observing the [[solar eclipse of June 30, 1973]].<ref name=\"Courier\" /> Flying on the Concorde, a group of scientists from Los Alamos and the Paris Observarory, including Liebenberg, remained in the path of totality for 74 minutes while conducting various scientific measurements of the corona.<ref name=\"Atlantic\" /><ref name=\"NPR\" /><ref name=\"Greenville\" /><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://permalink.lanl.gov/object/tr?what=info:lanl-repo/lareport/LA-UR-82-5105|title=In Flight: The Story of Los Alamos Eclipse Missions|first=Barb|last=Mulkin|journal=Los Alamos Science|accessdate=October 21, 2018}}</ref> For comparison, the theoretical maximum duration for totality during the third millennium for any stationary point or observer on the Earth's surface is approximately seven and a half minutes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meeus |first1=J |title=The maximum possible duration of a total solar eclipse |journal=Journal of the British Astronomical Association |volume=113 |page=344 (Table 1)|url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/2003JBAA..113..343M |accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe has worked as an adjunct professor in Clemson's department of physics and astronomy since 1996.<ref name=\"ClemNews\">{{cite web |last1=Melvin |first1=Jim |title=26 AND COUNTING / The Liebenberg Chronicles / Eclipse 9 / Part 2 of Concorde flight |url=http://newsstand.clemson.edu/26-and-counting-the-liebenberg-eclipse-chronicles-part-9/ |website=The Newsstand \u2013 Clemson University |accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nLiebenberg and his wife Norma<ref name=\"Courier\">{{cite news |last1=Borenstein |first1=Seth |title=Chasing eclipses across the globe is a way of life for some |url=https://www.postandcourier.com/solar_eclipse/chasing-eclipses-across-the-globe-is-a-way-of-life/article_aa94504e-83ba-11e7-8f31-6f0773d14e8e.html |accessdate=24 September 2018 |agency=The Post and Courier |date=17 August 2017}}</ref> reside in [[Salem, South Carolina]].<ref name=\"Atlantic\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.org/details/CSPAN2_20170818_041800_Interview_with_Donald_Liebenberg_on_the_Solar_Eclipse/start/0/end/60 Donald Liebenberg interview with CSPAN2]\n* [https://blogs.clemson.edu/eclipse/2017/06/25/26-and-counting-the-liebenberg-eclipse-chronicles-part-9/ Blog postings] where Liebenberg further discusses his experiences witnessing and researching solar eclipses\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liebenberg, Donald}}\n[[Category:Clemson University faculty]]\n[[Category:Los Alamos National Laboratory personnel]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1930s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Oconee County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin&ndash;Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:American astronomers]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer and eclipses:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Liebenberg"}
{"title_page": "Asma al-Ghul", "text_new": "{{unbalanced|date=July 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name          =  Asma al-Ghul\n|image         = Asma Alghoul 1.jpg\n|caption       = Asma Alghoul, 2011\n|birth_name    =\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1982|1|17}}\n|birth_place   =[[Rafah]]\n|death_date = \n|death_place   = \n|death_cause   = \n|resting_place =\n|resting_place_coordinates =\n|residence     = \n|nationality   =[[State of Palestine]]\n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = \n|education     =\n|employer      =[[Al-Ayyam (Ramallah)|Al-Ayyam]]\n|occupation    = [[Journalist]]\n|spouse         = \n|children       = \n|party         = \n|boards        =\n|parents       =\n|relatives     = \n|signature     =\n|website       =\n|footnotes     =\n}}\n'''Asma al-Ghul''' (also ''Al Ghoul'',  ''Alghoul'' ) is a young secular Palestinian feminist journalist who writes for the [[Ramallah]]-based newspaper [[Al-Ayyam (Ramallah)|Al-Ayyam]], chronicling what she calls \u201cthe corruption of Fatah and the terrorism of Hamas.\u201d<ref name=Bates>{{cite news|last=Bates|first=Ashley|title=Sorry, Hamas, I'm Wearing Blue Jeans|url=http://motherjones.com/politics/2010/12/gaza-hamas-asma-al-ghoul|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=Mother Jones magazine|date=16 December 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110531050435/http://motherjones.com/politics/2010/12/gaza-hamas-asma-al-ghoul| archivedate= 31 May 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> Al-Ayyam is sometimes banned in [[Gaza City|Gaza]] by [[Hamas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=al-Mughrabi|first=Nidal|title=Hamas bans Gaza newspaper over satirical cartoon|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/02/10/uk-palestinians-newspaper-idUKL1041459520080210|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=Reuters UK|date=10 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Palestinian daily Al-Ayyam, briefly banned in Gaza, appears again|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/palestinian-daily-al-ayyam-briefly-banned-in-gaza-appears-again-1.244959|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=Haaretz|date=30 April 2008}}</ref> Al-Ghul is described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"known for her defiant stance against violations of civil rights in Gaza.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Akram|first=Fares|title=Briefing on Protest for Palestinian Unity Becomes a Rally Itself|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/15/world/middleeast/15gaza.html|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=14 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAl-Ghul was born in 1982 in [[Rafah]], a Gazan city bordering [[Egypt]] whose population is mainly Palestinian refugees. In 2003, she married an Egyptian poet and moved to [[Abu Dhabi]]. She and her husband later divorced, and she returned to Gaza with their son. In 2006, al-Ghul permanently took off her Islamic [[khim\u0101r]] (headscarf).<ref name=Bates/>\n\nIn 2009, al-Ghul reported being stopped and interrogated by Hamas after walking on a public beach near the [[Al-Shati (camp)|Shati refugee camp]] in Gaza with a mixed-gender group of friends, while wearing jeans and a T-shirt with no headscarf, and laughing. The [[Associated Press]] said it was the first time since coming to power in 2007 that Hamas had tried to punish a woman for behaving in a way it viewed as un-Islamic.<ref name=msnbc>{{cite news|last=The Associated Press|title=Hamas tries to detain woman walking with man: Attempt raises fears of strict enforcement of Islamic law|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31793001|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=MSNBC|date=8 July 2009}}</ref> Al-Ghul says her male friends were subsequently detained for several hours, beaten, and then forced to sign statements saying they would not again \"violate public moral standards.\" Hamas has denied that the incident took place.<ref name=msnbc/>\n\nIn February 2011, al-Ghul said she was beaten while covering a rally expressing solidarity between Palestinians and Egyptians.<ref>{{cite web|title=CyberDissident Database: Palestinian Territories {{!}} Asma Al Ghoul|url=http://www.cyberdissidents.org/bin/dissidents.cgi?id=133&c=PS|publisher=CyberDissidents.org|accessdate=30 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725103541/http://www.cyberdissidents.org/bin/dissidents.cgi?id=133&c=PS|archive-date=25 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, al-Ghul and seven other female Palestinian journalists said they were beaten and tortured by Hamas security forces while trying to cover rallies calling for Hamas to seek a peaceful reconciliation with Fatah. The Hamas government later apologized for some of the attacks and promised to launch an investigation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Abu Toameh|first=Khaled|authorlink=Khaled Abu Toameh|title=Gaza cops use \u2018beatings, stun guns\u2019 on women reporters|url=http://www.jpost.com/MiddleEast/Article.aspx?id=214092|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|date=28 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Youth and Reconciliation: Tech-savvy women drive Gaza's protest movement|url=http://www.thedaily.com/page/2011/04/11/041111-news-gaza-youth-5-5/|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=The Daily|date=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 18, al-Ghul won the Palestinian Youth Literature award. In 2010, she received a [[Hellman/Hammett award]] from [[Human Rights Watch]], aimed at helping writers \"who dare to express ideas that criticize official public policy or people in power.\" Her work has been translated into English, Danish and Korean.<ref>{{cite web|title=Banned, Censored, Harassed and Jailed|url=https://www.hrw.org/en/news/2010/08/04/banned-censored-harassed-and-jailed|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=30 May 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110607183626/http://www.hrw.org/en/news/2010/08/04/banned-censored-harassed-and-jailed| archivedate= 7 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, al-Ghul was awarded the Courage in Journalism Award by the [[International Women's Media Foundation]].<ref name=\"thorn\">[http://www.jpost.com/Features/InThespotlight/Article.aspx?id=288991 \"Asmaa al-Ghoul aims to keep thorn in Hamas' side\"] in the ''Jerusalem Post'', October 23, 2012</ref> She works for Lebanon's [[Samir Kassir]] Foundation, which advocates for media freedom.<ref name=\"thorn\" />\n\nOn August 3, 2014, at least nine members from her family were killed in an Israeli airstrike, in Rafah, southern Gaza Strip.<ref name=\"familykilled\">[http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/08/rafah-gaza-war-hospitals-filled-bodies-palestinians.html# Never ask me about peace again] in the ''Al-Monitor, Palestine Pulse'', August 4, 2014</ref>  In an essay, al-Ghul documents her experiences after hearing the about the death of her family, entitled Never [http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/08/rafah-gaza-war-hospitals-filled-bodies-palestinians.html Ask Me About Peace Again].\n\nIn 2016, she published in french a book co-writing with S\u00e9lim Nassib, '[http://calmann-levy.fr/livres/linsoumise-de-gaza/ L'insoumise de Gaza]', translated in English in 2018 by Mike Mitchell, '[https://doppelhouse.com/a-rebel-in-gaza/ A Rebel in Gaza: Behind the Lines of the Arab Spring, One Woman\u2019s Story]'.\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Asma Alghoul}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghul, Asma}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Palestinian journalists]]\n[[Category:Palestinian feminists]]\n[[Category:Palestinian women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{unbalanced|date=July 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name          =  Asma al-Ghul\n|image         = Asma Alghoul 1.jpg\n|caption       = Asma Alghoul, 2011\n|birth_name    =\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1982|1|17}}\n|birth_place   =[[Rafah]]\n|death_date = \n|death_place   = \n|death_cause   = \n|resting_place =\n|resting_place_coordinates =\n|residence     = \n|nationality   =[[State of Palestine]]\n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = \n|education     =\n|employer      =[[Al-Ayyam (Ramallah)|Al-Ayyam]]\n|occupation    = [[Journalist]]\n|spouse         = \n|children       = \n|party         = \n|boards        =\n|parents       =\n|relatives     = \n|signature     =\n|website       =\n|footnotes     =\n}}\n'''Asma al-Ghul''' (also ''Al Ghoul'',  ''Alghoul'' ) is a young secular Palestinian feminist journalist who writes for the [[Ramallah]]-based newspaper [[Al-Ayyam (Ramallah)|Al-Ayyam]], chronicling what she calls \u201cthe corruption of Fatah and the terrorism of Hamas.\u201d<ref name=Bates>{{cite news|last=Bates|first=Ashley|title=Sorry, Hamas, I'm Wearing Blue Jeans|url=http://motherjones.com/politics/2010/12/gaza-hamas-asma-al-ghoul|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=Mother Jones magazine|date=16 December 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110531050435/http://motherjones.com/politics/2010/12/gaza-hamas-asma-al-ghoul| archivedate= 31 May 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> Al-Ayyam is sometimes banned in [[Gaza City|Gaza]] by [[Hamas]].<ref>{{cite news|last=al-Mughrabi|first=Nidal|title=Hamas bans Gaza newspaper over satirical cartoon|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/02/10/uk-palestinians-newspaper-idUKL1041459520080210|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=Reuters UK|date=10 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Palestinian daily Al-Ayyam, briefly banned in Gaza, appears again|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/palestinian-daily-al-ayyam-briefly-banned-in-gaza-appears-again-1.244959|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=Haaretz|date=30 April 2008}}</ref> Al-Ghul is described by the [[New York Times]] as \"known for her defiant stance against violations of civil rights in Gaza.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Akram|first=Fares|title=Briefing on Protest for Palestinian Unity Becomes a Rally Itself|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/15/world/middleeast/15gaza.html|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=14 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAl-Ghul was born in 1982 in [[Rafah]], a Gazan city bordering [[Egypt]] whose population is mainly Palestinian refugees. In 2003, she married an Egyptian poet and moved to [[Abu Dhabi]]. She and her husband later divorced, and she returned to Gaza with their son. In 2006, al-Ghul permanently took off her Islamic [[khim\u0101r]] (headscarf).<ref name=Bates/>\n\nIn 2009, al-Ghul reported being stopped and interrogated by Hamas after walking on a public beach near the [[Al-Shati (camp)|Shati refugee camp]] in Gaza with a mixed-gender group of friends, while wearing jeans and a T-shirt with no headscarf, and laughing. The [[Associated Press]] said it was the first time since coming to power in 2007 that Hamas had tried to punish a woman for behaving in a way it viewed as un-Islamic.<ref name=msnbc>{{cite news|last=The Associated Press|title=Hamas tries to detain woman walking with man: Attempt raises fears of strict enforcement of Islamic law|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31793001|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=MSNBC|date=8 July 2009}}</ref> Al-Ghul says her male friends were subsequently detained for several hours, beaten, and then forced to sign statements saying they would not again \"violate public moral standards.\" Hamas has denied that the incident took place.<ref name=msnbc/>\n\nIn February 2011, al-Ghul said she was beaten while covering a rally expressing solidarity between Palestinians and Egyptians.<ref>{{cite web|title=CyberDissident Database: Palestinian Territories {{!}} Asma Al Ghoul|url=http://www.cyberdissidents.org/bin/dissidents.cgi?id=133&c=PS|publisher=CyberDissidents.org|accessdate=30 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725103541/http://www.cyberdissidents.org/bin/dissidents.cgi?id=133&c=PS|archive-date=25 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, al-Ghul and seven other female Palestinian journalists said they were beaten and tortured by Hamas security forces while trying to cover rallies calling for Hamas to seek a peaceful reconciliation with Fatah. The Hamas government later apologized for some of the attacks and promised to launch an investigation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Abu Toameh|first=Khaled|authorlink=Khaled Abu Toameh|title=Gaza cops use \u2018beatings, stun guns\u2019 on women reporters|url=http://www.jpost.com/MiddleEast/Article.aspx?id=214092|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|date=28 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Youth and Reconciliation: Tech-savvy women drive Gaza's protest movement|url=http://www.thedaily.com/page/2011/04/11/041111-news-gaza-youth-5-5/|accessdate=30 May 2011|newspaper=The Daily|date=11 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 18, al-Ghul won the Palestinian Youth Literature award. In 2010, she received a [[Hellman/Hammett award]] from [[Human Rights Watch]], aimed at helping writers \"who dare to express ideas that criticize official public policy or people in power.\" Her work has been translated into English, Danish and Korean.<ref>{{cite web|title=Banned, Censored, Harassed and Jailed|url=https://www.hrw.org/en/news/2010/08/04/banned-censored-harassed-and-jailed|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=30 May 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110607183626/http://www.hrw.org/en/news/2010/08/04/banned-censored-harassed-and-jailed| archivedate= 7 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, al-Ghul was awarded the Courage in Journalism Award by the [[International Women's Media Foundation]].<ref name=\"thorn\">[http://www.jpost.com/Features/InThespotlight/Article.aspx?id=288991 \"Asmaa al-Ghoul aims to keep thorn in Hamas' side\"] in the ''Jerusalem Post'', October 23, 2012</ref> She works for Lebanon's [[Samir Kassir]] Foundation, which advocates for media freedom.<ref name=\"thorn\" />\n\nOn August 3, 2014, at least nine members from her family were killed in an Israeli airstrike, in Rafah, southern Gaza Strip.<ref name=\"familykilled\">[http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/08/rafah-gaza-war-hospitals-filled-bodies-palestinians.html# Never ask me about peace again] in the ''Al-Monitor, Palestine Pulse'', August 4, 2014</ref>  In an essay, al-Ghul documents her experiences after hearing the about the death of her family, entitled Never [http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/08/rafah-gaza-war-hospitals-filled-bodies-palestinians.html Ask Me About Peace Again].\n\nIn 2016, she published in french a book co-writing with S\u00e9lim Nassib, '[http://calmann-levy.fr/livres/linsoumise-de-gaza/ L'insoumise de Gaza]', translated in English in 2018 by Mike Mitchell, '[https://doppelhouse.com/a-rebel-in-gaza/ A Rebel in Gaza: Behind the Lines of the Arab Spring, One Woman\u2019s Story]'.\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Asma Alghoul}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghul, Asma}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Palestinian journalists]]\n[[Category:Palestinian feminists]]\n[[Category:Palestinian women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asma_al-Ghul"}
{"title_page": "Philippa Browning", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Philippa Browning\n| birth_name = Philippa K. Browning\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FInstP|size=100%}}\n| workplaces = [[University of Manchester]]<br>[[University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology]]\n| education = [[Millfield]]<ref name=millfield/>\n| alma_mater = [[University of Cambridge]] (BA)<br>[[University of St Andrews]] (PhD)\n| awards = [[Chapman Medal]] (2016)\n| fields = [[Astrophysics]]<br>[[Solar physics]]\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Eric Priest]]<ref name=bphd/>\n| thesis_title = Inhomogeneous magnetic fields in the solar atmosphere\n| thesis_url = http://hdl.handle.net/10023/3830\n| website= {{URL|www.jodrellbank.manchester.ac.uk/people/staff-spotlights/philippa-browning}}\n}}\n\n'''Philippa K. Browning''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FInstP}} is a Professor of Astrophysics in the [[Jodrell Bank Centre for Astrophysics]] at the [[University of Manchester]].<ref name=jod/> She specialises in the mathematical modelling of fusion [[Plasma (physics)|plasmas]].<ref name=pkb/>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBrowning was educated at [[Millfield]]<ref name=millfield>{{cite journal|last1=Browning|first1=Philippa|title=Q&A Philippa Browning|journal=Astronomy & Geophysics|volume=58|issue=1|year=2017|pages=1.43|issn=1366-8781|doi=10.1093/astrogeo/atx029}}</ref> and studied the [[Mathematical Tripos]] at the [[University of Cambridge]], graduating in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://msas.org.uk/about/programme/speaker/44|title=MSAS Our Programme|website=msas.org.uk|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She completed [[Part III of the Mathematical Tripos]] in 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Extras/YRM.html|title=Young Researchers|website=www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She was inspired by [[Yuri Gagarin]] to work in astrophysics.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.se.manchester.ac.uk/people/women-of-wonder/philippa-browning/|title=Philippa Browning: Science and Engineering |publisher=University of Manchester  |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|author=Anon|title=Women of Wonder: Prof Philippa Browning|date=9 August 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ayFWRSWZGbw|access-date=16 September 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> For her graduate studies Browning joined the [[University of St Andrews]] working with [[Eric Priest]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Priest|first=E. R.|year=2014|title=A Life of Fun Playing with Solar Magnetic Fields (Special Historical Review)|journal=Solar Physics|volume=289|issue=10|pages=3579\u20133615|doi=10.1007/s11207-014-0554-2|issn=0038-0938|arxiv=1405.3481|bibcode=2014SoPh..289.3579P}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.st-andrews.ac.uk/archive/conference-honours-professor/|title=Conference honours Professor|website=news.st-andrews.ac.uk|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She submitted her thesis on ''Inhomogeneous Magnetic Fields in the Solar Atmosphere'' in 1984.<ref name=bphd>{{Cite thesis|degree=PhD|publisher=University of St Andrews|year=1984|first=Philippa K.|last=Browning|title=Inhomogeneous magnetic fields in the solar atmosphere|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.349463}}|hdl=10023/3830|oclc=890152927}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nAfter completing her PhD Browning worked as a [[postdoctoral researcher]] with [[Eric Priest]].<ref name=\":1\" /> She studied [[coronal loop]]s, finding they were a balance of [[magnetic tension force]]s, buoyancy and [[pressure gradient]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Browning|first=P. K.|last2=Priest|first2=E. R.|year=1986|title=The shape of buoyant coronal loops in a magnetic field and the eruption of coronal transients and prominences|journal=Solar Physics|volume=106|issue=2|pages=335\u2013351|doi=10.1007/bf00158500|issn=0038-0938|bibcode=1986SoPh..106..335B}}</ref> Her work covered the fundamentals of [[flux tube]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Browning|first=P. K.|last2=Priest|first2=E. R.|year=1983|title=Structure of twisted magnetic flux tubes|journal=Astrophysical Journal|volume=266|issue=2|pages=848\u2013865|issn=0004-637X|doi=10.1086/160833|bibcode=1983ApJ...266..848B}}</ref> Browning was appointed a lecturer at [[University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology]] (UMIST) in 1985.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} She joined the [[University of Manchester]] in 2004, where she works on the interactions between plasmas and magnetic fields.<ref name=jod>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jodrellbank.manchester.ac.uk/people/staff-spotlights/philippa-browning/|title=Philippa Browning |publisher=University of Manchester |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She is particularly interested in solar flares.<ref>{{Citation|last=1988\u2013|first=Iliadis, Dennis. Gullo, Bill. Wakefield, Rhys, 1988\u2013 Miller, Logan, 1992\u2013 Hinshaw, Ashley, 1988\u2013 Hall, Natalie|title=+1|isbn=978-0788617539|oclc=867735697}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/whatson/event/?eventno=34008|title=Philippa Browning on Solar Flares |publisher=Durham University|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zharkova|first=V. V.|last2=Arzner|first2=K.|last3=Benz|first3=A. O.|last4=Browning|first4=P.|last5=Dauphin|first5=C.|last6=Emslie|first6=A. G.|last7=Fletcher|first7=L.|last8=Kontar|first8=E. P.|last9=Mann|first9=G.|year=2011|title=Recent Advances in Understanding Particle Acceleration Processes in Solar Flares|journal=Space Science Reviews|volume=159|issue=1\u20134|pages=357\u2013420|doi=10.1007/s11214-011-9803-y|issn=0038-6308|citeseerx=10.1.1.749.591|bibcode=2011SSRv..159..357Z|arxiv=1110.2359}}</ref> In 2009, Browning was promoted to professor at the [[Jodrell Bank Centre for Astrophysics]].<ref name=pkb>{{Cite web|url=https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/philippa.browning.html|title=Prof Philippa Browning |publisher=University of Manchester|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She served as editor of the ''[[Journal of Geophysical Research]]'' from 2010 to 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/hub/journal/21699402/previous-editors.html|title=Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics |website=agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She contributed to the book ''Multi-scale Dynamical Processes in Space and Astrophysical Plasmas''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Multi-scale Dynamical Processes in Space and Astrophysical Plasmas|last=Leubner|first=Manfred P.|last2=V\u00f6r\u00f6s|first2=Zolt\u00e1n|date=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9783642304415|language=en}}</ref> She continues to study [[solar corona|coronal]] heating.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=De Moortel|first=Ineke|last2=Browning|first2=Philippa|year=2015|title=Recent advances in coronal heating|arxiv=1510.00977|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences|volume=373|issue=2042|pages=20140269|doi=10.1098/rsta.2014.0269|pmid=25897095|pmc=4410557|issn=1364-503X|bibcode=2015RSPTA.37340269D}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moortel|first=Ineke De|last2=Browning|first2=Philippa|year=2015|title=Recent advances in coronal heating|journal=Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A|volume=373|issue=2042|pages=20140269|doi=10.1098/rsta.2014.0269|issn=1364-503X|pmid=25897095|pmc=4410557|bibcode=2015RSPTA.37340269D|arxiv=1510.00977}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Browning was made chair of the [[Institute of Physics]] Plasma Physics Committee and the Solar Physics Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/physics/news/physicsdays/events/solartokamak14/|title=Synergy between Solar and Tokamak Plasma Theory|publisher=University of Warwick|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> Through the Solar Physics Council, Browning is a mentor for young solar physicists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uksolphys.org/mentors/|title=Mentors |website=uksolphys.org|publisher= UK Solar Physics|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> In 2014 Browning arranged two-day meeting to discuss [[Coronal heating problem|coronal heating]] at the [[Royal Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/science-events-and-lectures/2014/coronal-heating/|title=New approaches in coronal heating|author=Anon|year=2014 |website=royalsociety.org|publisher=[[Royal Society]]|location=London|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}} Browning is working on the [[Solar Orbiter]] and [[Parker Solar Probe]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Browning has appeared at the [[Bluedot Festival]]. She discussed her work on [[solar flare]]s and their interaction with the earth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discoverthebluedot.com/profile/philippa-browning|title=Philippa Browning|website=discoverthebluedot.com|publisher=Bluedot Festival|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She has taken part in the [[Manchester Science Festival]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestersciencefestival.com/event/8-minutes/|title=8 Minutes |work=Manchester Science Festival|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> Browning serves on the [[Institute of Physics]] Women in Physics advisory panel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iop.org/activity/groups/subject/wip/panel/page_59562.html|title=WIPG Advisory Panel|last=Physics|first=Institute of|website=iop.org|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honours===\nBrowning was awarded the [[Chapman Medal]] by the [[Royal Astronomical Society]] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ras.org.uk/awards-and-grants/awards/2999-winners-of-the-2016-awards-medals-and-prizes-full-details|title=Winners of the 2016 awards, medals and prizes \u2013 full details|last=Hollis|first=Morgan|year=2016|website=ras.org.uk|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stfc.ukri.org/news/stfc-supported-scientists-awarded-for-geophysics-and-astronomy-work/|title=STFC-supported scientists awarded for geophysics and astronomy work |website=stfc.ukri.org|publisher= Science and Technology Facilities Council|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> The medal recognised her \"pioneering work on energy release by magnetic relaxation in stressed coronal magnetic fields\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iop.org/news/16/jan/page_66846.html|year=2016|title=Royal Astronomical Society medals go to IOP members|author=Anon|website=iop.org|publisher=Institute of Physics|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> In 2017 she was awarded a [[Science and Technology Facilities Council]] (STFC) research grant to explore particle acceleration in twisted magnetic fields.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/grant-winners-20-april-2017|title=Grant winners \u2013 20 April 2017|year=2017|author=Anon|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She was elected a [[Fellow of the Institute of Physics]] (FInstP).{{when|date=September 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Browning Philippa}}\n[[Category:British astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:British astronomers]]\n[[Category:Women astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Institute of Physics]]\n[[Category:British women physicists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Millfield]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Philippa Browning\n| birth_name = Philippa K. Browning\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FInstP|size=100%}}\n| workplaces = [[University of Manchester]]<br>[[University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology]]\n| education = [[Millfield]]<ref name=millfield/>\n| alma_mater = [[University of Cambridge]] (BA)<br>[[University of St Andrews]] (PhD)\n| awards = [[Chapman Medal]] (2016)\n| fields = [[Astrophysics]]<br>[[Solar physics]]\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Eric Priest]]<ref name=bphd/>\n| thesis_title = Inhomogeneous magnetic fields in the solar atmosphere\n| thesis_url = http://hdl.handle.net/10023/3830\n| website= {{URL|www.jodrellbank.manchester.ac.uk/people/staff-spotlights/philippa-browning}}\n}}\n\n'''Philippa K. Browning''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FInstP}} is a Professor of Astrophysics in the [[Jodrell Bank Centre for Astrophysics]] at the [[University of Manchester]].<ref name=jod/> She specialises in the mathematical modelling of fusion [[Plasma (physics)|plasmas]].<ref name=pkb/>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBrowning was educated at [[Millfield]]<ref name=millfield>{{cite journal|last1=Browning|first1=Philippa|title=Q&A Philippa Browning|journal=Astronomy & Geophysics|volume=58|issue=1|year=2017|pages=1.43|issn=1366-8781|doi=10.1093/astrogeo/atx029}}</ref> and studied the [[Mathematical Tripos]] at the [[University of Cambridge]], graduating in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://msas.org.uk/about/programme/speaker/44|title=MSAS Our Programme|website=msas.org.uk|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She completed [[Part III of the Mathematical Tripos]] in 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Extras/YRM.html|title=Young Researchers|website=www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She was inspired by [[Yuri Gagarin]] to work in astrophysics.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.se.manchester.ac.uk/people/women-of-wonder/philippa-browning/|title=Philippa Browning: Science and Engineering |publisher=University of Manchester  |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|author=Anon|title=Women of Wonder: Prof Philippa Browning|date=9 August 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ayFWRSWZGbw|access-date=16 September 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> For her graduate studies Browning joined the [[University of St Andrews]] working with [[Eric Priest]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Priest|first=E. R.|year=2014|title=A Life of Fun Playing with Solar Magnetic Fields (Special Historical Review)|journal=Solar Physics|volume=289|issue=10|pages=3579\u20133615|doi=10.1007/s11207-014-0554-2|issn=0038-0938|arxiv=1405.3481|bibcode=2014SoPh..289.3579P}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.st-andrews.ac.uk/archive/conference-honours-professor/|title=Conference honours Professor|website=news.st-andrews.ac.uk|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She submitted her thesis on ''Inhomogeneous Magnetic Fields in the Solar Atmosphere'' in 1984.<ref name=bphd>{{Cite thesis|degree=PhD|publisher=University of St Andrews|year=1984|first=Philippa K.|last=Browning|title=Inhomogeneous magnetic fields in the solar atmosphere|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.349463}}|hdl=10023/3830|oclc=890152927}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nAfter completing her PhD Browning worked as a [[postdoctoral researcher]] with [[Eric Priest]].<ref name=\":1\" /> She studied [[coronal loop]]s, finding they were a balance of [[magnetic tension force]]s, buoyancy and [[pressure gradient]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Browning|first=P. K.|last2=Priest|first2=E. R.|year=1986|title=The shape of buoyant coronal loops in a magnetic field and the eruption of coronal transients and prominences|journal=Solar Physics|volume=106|issue=2|pages=335\u2013351|doi=10.1007/bf00158500|issn=0038-0938|bibcode=1986SoPh..106..335B}}</ref> Her work covered the fundamentals of [[flux tube]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Browning|first=P. K.|last2=Priest|first2=E. R.|year=1983|title=Structure of twisted magnetic flux tubes|journal=Astrophysical Journal|volume=266|issue=2|pages=848\u2013865|issn=0004-637X|doi=10.1086/160833|bibcode=1983ApJ...266..848B}}</ref> Browning was appointed a lecturer at [[University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology]] (UMIST) in 1985.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} She joined the [[University of Manchester]] in 2004, where she works on the interactions between plasmas and magnetic fields.<ref name=jod>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jodrellbank.manchester.ac.uk/people/staff-spotlights/philippa-browning/|title=Philippa Browning |publisher=University of Manchester |access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She is particularly interested in solar flares.<ref>{{Citation|last=1988\u2013|first=Iliadis, Dennis. Gullo, Bill. Wakefield, Rhys, 1988\u2013 Miller, Logan, 1992\u2013 Hinshaw, Ashley, 1988\u2013 Hall, Natalie|title=+1|isbn=978-0788617539|oclc=867735697}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/whatson/event/?eventno=34008|title=Philippa Browning on Solar Flares |publisher=Durham University|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zharkova|first=V. V.|last2=Arzner|first2=K.|last3=Benz|first3=A. O.|last4=Browning|first4=P.|last5=Dauphin|first5=C.|last6=Emslie|first6=A. G.|last7=Fletcher|first7=L.|last8=Kontar|first8=E. P.|last9=Mann|first9=G.|year=2011|title=Recent Advances in Understanding Particle Acceleration Processes in Solar Flares|journal=Space Science Reviews|volume=159|issue=1\u20134|pages=357\u2013420|doi=10.1007/s11214-011-9803-y|issn=0038-6308|citeseerx=10.1.1.749.591|bibcode=2011SSRv..159..357Z|arxiv=1110.2359}}</ref> In 2009, Browning was promoted to professor at the [[Jodrell Bank Centre for Astrophysics]].<ref name=pkb>{{Cite web|url=https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/philippa.browning.html|title=Prof Philippa Browning |publisher=University of Manchester|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She served as editor of the ''[[Journal of Geophysical Research]]'' from 2010 to 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/hub/journal/21699402/previous-editors.html|title=Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics |website=agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She contributed to the book ''Multi-scale Dynamical Processes in Space and Astrophysical Plasmas''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Multi-scale Dynamical Processes in Space and Astrophysical Plasmas|last=Leubner|first=Manfred P.|last2=V\u00f6r\u00f6s|first2=Zolt\u00e1n|date=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9783642304415|language=en}}</ref> She continues to study [[corona]]l heating.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=De Moortel|first=Ineke|last2=Browning|first2=Philippa|year=2015|title=Recent advances in coronal heating|arxiv=1510.00977|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences|volume=373|issue=2042|pages=20140269|doi=10.1098/rsta.2014.0269|pmid=25897095|pmc=4410557|issn=1364-503X|bibcode=2015RSPTA.37340269D}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moortel|first=Ineke De|last2=Browning|first2=Philippa|year=2015|title=Recent advances in coronal heating|journal=Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A|volume=373|issue=2042|pages=20140269|doi=10.1098/rsta.2014.0269|issn=1364-503X|pmid=25897095|pmc=4410557|bibcode=2015RSPTA.37340269D|arxiv=1510.00977}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Browning was made chair of the [[Institute of Physics]] Plasma Physics Committee and the Solar Physics Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/physics/news/physicsdays/events/solartokamak14/|title=Synergy between Solar and Tokamak Plasma Theory|publisher=University of Warwick|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> Through the Solar Physics Council, Browning is a mentor for young solar physicists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uksolphys.org/mentors/|title=Mentors |website=uksolphys.org|publisher= UK Solar Physics|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> In 2014 Browning arranged two-day meeting to discuss [[Coronal heating problem|coronal heating]] at the [[Royal Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/science-events-and-lectures/2014/coronal-heating/|title=New approaches in coronal heating|author=Anon|year=2014 |website=royalsociety.org|publisher=[[Royal Society]]|location=London|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}} Browning is working on the [[Solar Orbiter]] and [[Parker Solar Probe]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Browning has appeared at the [[Bluedot Festival]]. She discussed her work on [[solar flare]]s and their interaction with the earth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discoverthebluedot.com/profile/philippa-browning|title=Philippa Browning|website=discoverthebluedot.com|publisher=Bluedot Festival|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She has taken part in the [[Manchester Science Festival]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestersciencefestival.com/event/8-minutes/|title=8 Minutes |work=Manchester Science Festival|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> Browning serves on the [[Institute of Physics]] Women in Physics advisory panel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iop.org/activity/groups/subject/wip/panel/page_59562.html|title=WIPG Advisory Panel|last=Physics|first=Institute of|website=iop.org|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honours===\nBrowning was awarded the [[Chapman Medal]] by the [[Royal Astronomical Society]] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ras.org.uk/awards-and-grants/awards/2999-winners-of-the-2016-awards-medals-and-prizes-full-details|title=Winners of the 2016 awards, medals and prizes \u2013 full details|last=Hollis|first=Morgan|year=2016|website=ras.org.uk|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stfc.ukri.org/news/stfc-supported-scientists-awarded-for-geophysics-and-astronomy-work/|title=STFC-supported scientists awarded for geophysics and astronomy work |website=stfc.ukri.org|publisher= Science and Technology Facilities Council|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> The medal recognised her \"pioneering work on energy release by magnetic relaxation in stressed coronal magnetic fields\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iop.org/news/16/jan/page_66846.html|year=2016|title=Royal Astronomical Society medals go to IOP members|author=Anon|website=iop.org|publisher=Institute of Physics|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> In 2017 she was awarded a [[Science and Technology Facilities Council]] (STFC) research grant to explore particle acceleration in twisted magnetic fields.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/grant-winners-20-april-2017|title=Grant winners \u2013 20 April 2017|year=2017|author=Anon|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|access-date=16 September 2018}}</ref> She was elected a [[Fellow of the Institute of Physics]] (FInstP).{{when|date=September 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Browning Philippa}}\n[[Category:British astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:British astronomers]]\n[[Category:Women astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Institute of Physics]]\n[[Category:British women physicists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Millfield]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResearch and career:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippa_Browning"}
{"title_page": "WISPR", "text_new": "[[File:Parker-Solar-Probe-WISPR.png|thumb|275px|Diagram of WISPR]]\nThe '''Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe''' ('''WISPR''') is an imaging instrument of the ''[[Parker Solar Probe]]'' mission to the [[Sun]], launched in August 2018.<ref name=\"svs12927\">{{Cite web |url=https://svs.gsfc.nasa.gov/12927 |title=Looking at the Corona with WISPR on Parker Solar Probe |publisher=NASA/Goddard Media Studios |date=16 April 2018 |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> Imaging targets include visible light images of the [[solar corona|corona]], [[solar wind]], shocks, solar ejecta, etc.<ref name=\"svs12927\" /> Development of WISPR was led by the  [[U.S. Naval Research Laboratory]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=106691 |title=NRL's Sun Imaging Telescopes Fly on NASA Parker Solar Probe |publisher=U.S. Navy |date=10 August 2018 |access-date=14 September 2018 |id=NNS180810-19}}</ref> The ''Parker Solar Probe'' with WISPR on board was launched by a [[Delta IV Heavy]] on 12 August 2018 from [[Cape Canaveral]], Florida.<ref name=launch>{{Cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=94 |title=Parker Solar Probe Launches on Historic Journey to Touch the Sun |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory |last1=Brown |first1=Geoffrey |last2=Brown |first2=Dwayne |last3=Fox |first3=Karen |date=12 August 2018 |access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref> WISPR is intended take advantage of the spacecraft's proximity to the Sun by taking [[coronagraph]]-style images of the solar corona and features like coronal streamers, plumes, and [[Coronal mass ejection|mass ejections]].<ref name=\"nrl20180810\">{{cite web |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=106691 |title=NRL's Sun Imaging Telescopes Fly on NASA Parker Solar Probe |publisher=U.S. Navy/Naval Research Laboratory |date=10 August 2018 |accessdate=7 October 2018 |id=NNS180810-19}}</ref> One of the goals is to better understand the structure of the solar corona near the Sun.<ref name=\"nrl20180810\"/>\n\nWISPR is designed to study the [[electron density]] and velocity structure of the corona.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nrl.navy.mil/ssd/branches/7680/WISPR |title=Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe Plus (WISPR) |publisher=U.S. Navy/Naval Research Laboratory |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> The instrument field of view is planned to extend from 13 to 108 degrees away from the Sun, and does not directly image the Sun; the area of interest is a very wide field extending away from the Sun.<ref name=\"svs12927\" />\n\nWISPR includes two separate telescopes, each with a [[Radiation hardening|radiation-hardened]] [[CMOS]] imager with resolution of 2,000\u00d72,000 pixels.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sri.com/work/projects/wide-field-imager-solar-probe-wispr |title=Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe (WISPR) |publisher=SRI International |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> The CMOS sensors are an [[active pixel sensor]] type of detector.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/parker-solar-probe-instruments |title=Parker Solar Probe Instruments |publisher=NASA |editor-last=Garner |editor-first=Rob |date=12 July 2018 |access-date=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe WISPR [[first light (astronomy)|first light]] image was published in September 2018.<ref name=\"JHUAPL\">{{Cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=101 |title=Illuminating First Light Data from Parker Solar Probe |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory |first1=Sarah |last1=Frazier |first2=Justyna |last2=Surowiec |date=19 September 2018 |access-date=22 September 2018}}</ref> In December, a view of the corona including a coronal streamer was released.<ref name=\"parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu\">{{Cite web|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=115|title=Preparing for Discovery With NASA's Parker Solar Probe|last=JHUAPL|website=Parker Solar Probe|language=en|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, a video of WIPSR recording solar wind during the spacecraft's first close pass to the Sun was released.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2019/one-year-2-trips-around-sun-for-nasas-parker-solar-probe|title=One Year, 2 Trips Around Sun for NASA's Parker Solar Probe|last=Garner|first=Rob|date=2019-08-12|website=NASA|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> One project scientist noted, \"The data we\u2019re seeing from Parker Solar Probe\u2019s instruments is showing us details about solar structures and processes that we have never seen before,\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Development ==\nThe [[stray light]] and baffle for WISPR was modeled during development of the instrument.<ref>M.-L. Hellin, E. Mazy, S. Marcotte, Y. Stockman, C. Korendyke, A. Thernisien, \"Stray light testing of WISPR baffle development model,\" Proc. SPIE 10562, International Conference on Space Optics \u2014 ICSO 2016, 105624V (25 September 2017); https://www.spiedigitallibrary.org/conference-proceedings-of-spie/10562/105624V/Stray-light-testing-of-WISPR-baffle-development-model/10.1117/12.2296104.full?SSO=1</ref> Two noted cases where stray material caused issue with space imaging includes the Infrared Telescope (IRT) flown on the Space Shuttle [[Spacelab]]-2 mission, in which a piece of [[mylar]] insulation broke loose and floated into the line-of-sight of the telescope corrupting data.<ref name=\"kent\">[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1992ApJS...78..403K Kent, et al. \u2013 '''Galactic structure from the Spacelab infrared telescope''' (1992)].</ref> This was on the [[STS-51-F]] in the year 1985.<ref name=\"kent\" /> Another case was in the 2010s on the Gaia spacecraft for which some stray light was identified coming from fibers of the sunshield, protruding beyond the edges of the shield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cosmos.esa.int/web/gaia/news_20141217|title=STATUS OF THE GAIA STRAYLIGHT ANALYSIS AND MITIGATION ACTIONS|date=2014-12-17|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n;First light in space\n[[File:WISPR first light image.png|thumb|400px|left|WISPR first light image. The right portion of the image is from WISPR's inner telescope, which is a 40-degree field of view and begins 58.5 degrees from the Sun's center. The left portion is from the outer telescope, which is a 58-degree field of view and ends about 160 degrees from the Sun.<ref name=\"JHUAPL\"/>]]\n{{clear}}\n;First coronal view\nIn December WISPR's a view of the corona was published, including a coronal streamer.<ref name=\"parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[FIELDS]]\n*[[ISIS (space probe instrument)|IS\u2609IS]]\n*[[SWEAP]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://svs.gsfc.nasa.gov/12927 Looking at the Corona with WISPR on Parker Solar Probe] (April 16, 2018)\n\n{{Psp}}\n\n[[Category:Parker Solar Probe]]\n[[Category:Space imagers]]\n[[Category:Solar telescopes]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Parker-Solar-Probe-WISPR.png|thumb|275px|Diagram of WISPR]]\nThe '''Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe''' ('''WISPR''') is an imaging instrument of the ''[[Parker Solar Probe]]'' mission to the [[Sun]], launched in August 2018.<ref name=\"svs12927\">{{Cite web |url=https://svs.gsfc.nasa.gov/12927 |title=Looking at the Corona with WISPR on Parker Solar Probe |publisher=NASA/Goddard Media Studios |date=16 April 2018 |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> Imaging targets include visible light images of the [[corona]], [[solar wind]], shocks, solar ejecta, etc.<ref name=\"svs12927\" /> Development of WISPR was led by the  [[U.S. Naval Research Laboratory]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=106691 |title=NRL's Sun Imaging Telescopes Fly on NASA Parker Solar Probe |publisher=U.S. Navy |date=10 August 2018 |access-date=14 September 2018 |id=NNS180810-19}}</ref> The ''Parker Solar Probe'' with WISPR on board was launched by a [[Delta IV Heavy]] on 12 August 2018 from [[Cape Canaveral]], Florida.<ref name=launch>{{Cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=94 |title=Parker Solar Probe Launches on Historic Journey to Touch the Sun |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory |last1=Brown |first1=Geoffrey |last2=Brown |first2=Dwayne |last3=Fox |first3=Karen |date=12 August 2018 |access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref> WISPR is intended take advantage of the spacecraft's proximity to the Sun by taking [[coronagraph]]-style images of the solar corona and features like coronal streamers, plumes, and [[Coronal mass ejection|mass ejections]].<ref name=\"nrl20180810\">{{cite web |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=106691 |title=NRL's Sun Imaging Telescopes Fly on NASA Parker Solar Probe |publisher=U.S. Navy/Naval Research Laboratory |date=10 August 2018 |accessdate=7 October 2018 |id=NNS180810-19}}</ref> One of the goals is to better understand the structure of the solar corona near the Sun.<ref name=\"nrl20180810\"/>\n\nWISPR is designed to study the [[electron density]] and velocity structure of the corona.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nrl.navy.mil/ssd/branches/7680/WISPR |title=Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe Plus (WISPR) |publisher=U.S. Navy/Naval Research Laboratory |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> The instrument field of view is planned to extend from 13 to 108 degrees away from the Sun, and does not directly image the Sun; the area of interest is a very wide field extending away from the Sun.<ref name=\"svs12927\" />\n\nWISPR includes two separate telescopes, each with a [[Radiation hardening|radiation-hardened]] [[CMOS]] imager with resolution of 2,000\u00d72,000 pixels.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sri.com/work/projects/wide-field-imager-solar-probe-wispr |title=Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe (WISPR) |publisher=SRI International |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> The CMOS sensors are an [[active pixel sensor]] type of detector.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/parker-solar-probe-instruments |title=Parker Solar Probe Instruments |publisher=NASA |editor-last=Garner |editor-first=Rob |date=12 July 2018 |access-date=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe WISPR [[first light (astronomy)|first light]] image was published in September 2018.<ref name=\"JHUAPL\">{{Cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=101 |title=Illuminating First Light Data from Parker Solar Probe |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory |first1=Sarah |last1=Frazier |first2=Justyna |last2=Surowiec |date=19 September 2018 |access-date=22 September 2018}}</ref> In December, a view of the corona including a coronal streamer was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=115|title=Preparing for Discovery With NASA's Parker Solar Probe|last=JHUAPL|website=Parker Solar Probe|language=en|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, a video of WIPSR recording solar wind during the spacecraft's first close pass to the Sun was released.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2019/one-year-2-trips-around-sun-for-nasas-parker-solar-probe|title=One Year, 2 Trips Around Sun for NASA's Parker Solar Probe|last=Garner|first=Rob|date=2019-08-12|website=NASA|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref> One project scientist noted, \"The data we\u2019re seeing from Parker Solar Probe\u2019s instruments is showing us details about solar structures and processes that we have never seen before,\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Development ==\nThe [[stray light]] and baffle for WISPR was modeled during development of the instrument.<ref>M.-L. Hellin, E. Mazy, S. Marcotte, Y. Stockman, C. Korendyke, A. Thernisien, \"Stray light testing of WISPR baffle development model,\" Proc. SPIE 10562, International Conference on Space Optics \u2014 ICSO 2016, 105624V (25 September 2017); https://www.spiedigitallibrary.org/conference-proceedings-of-spie/10562/105624V/Stray-light-testing-of-WISPR-baffle-development-model/10.1117/12.2296104.full?SSO=1</ref> Two noted cases where stray material caused issue with space imaging includes the Infrared Telescope (IRT) flown on the Space Shuttle [[Spacelab]]-2 mission, in which a piece of [[mylar]] insulation broke loose and floated into the line-of-sight of the telescope corrupting data.<ref name=\"kent\">[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1992ApJS...78..403K Kent, et al. \u2013 '''Galactic structure from the Spacelab infrared telescope''' (1992)].</ref> This was on the [[STS-51-F]] in the year 1985.<ref name=\"kent\" /> Another case was in the 2010s on the Gaia spacecraft for which some stray light was identified coming from fibers of the sunshield, protruding beyond the edges of the shield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cosmos.esa.int/web/gaia/news_20141217|title=STATUS OF THE GAIA STRAYLIGHT ANALYSIS AND MITIGATION ACTIONS|date=2014-12-17|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n;First light in space\n[[File:WISPR first light image.png|thumb|400px|left|WISPR first light image. The right portion of the image is from WISPR's inner telescope, which is a 40-degree field of view and begins 58.5 degrees from the Sun's center. The left portion is from the outer telescope, which is a 58-degree field of view and ends about 160 degrees from the Sun.<ref name=\"JHUAPL\"/>]]\n{{clear}}\n;First coronal view\nIn December WISPR's a view of the corona was published, including a coronal streamer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=115|title=Preparing for Discovery With NASA's Parker Solar Probe|last=JHUAPL|website=Parker Solar Probe|language=en|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[FIELDS]]\n*[[ISIS (space probe instrument)|IS\u2609IS]]\n*[[SWEAP]]\n\n==References==\n