{"title_page": "Horia Sima", "text_new": "{{Expand Romanian|Horia Sima|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Horia Sima\n| honorific-prefix = \n| image = Horia Sima.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| order = [[Conduc\u0103tor|Co-Conducator]] of Romania\n| term_start = 14 September 1940\n| alongside = [[Ion Antonescu]]&nbsp;\n| term_end = 14 February 1941\n| predecessor = [[Carol II of Romania|Carol II]] (''as [[King of Romania]]'')\n| successor = Ion Antonescu (''as sole Conduc\u0103tor'')\n| vicepresident = \n| deputy = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1907|07|03}}\n| birth_place = [[F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219]], [[Lands of the Crown of Saint Stephen|Transleithania]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1993|05|25|1907|07|03}}\n| death_place = [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n| death_cause = \n| constituency = \n| nationality = [[Romania|Romanian]]\n| party = [[Iron Guard]]\n| spouse = \n| profession = \n| religion = [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]]\n}}\n{{Fascism in Romania}}\n'''Horia Sima''' (3 July 1907 &ndash; 25 May 1993) was a [[Romania|Romanian]] [[fascist]] politician, best known as the second and last leader of the fascist paramilitary movement known as the [[Iron Guard]], also known as the ''Legion of the Archangel Michael''. Sima was also the vice president of the council of ministers in [[Ion Antonescu]]'s [[National Legionary State]], and a short-lived minister in the government of [[Ion Gigurtu]]. In January 1941, Sima initiated and led the [[Legionnaires' rebellion and Bucharest pogrom|Legionnaires' Rebellion]] against [[Conduc\u0103tor]] Ion Antonescu and the Romanian Army, for which he was sentenced to death, as well as the [[Legionnaires' rebellion and Bucharest pogrom|Bucharest pogrom]], the largest and most violent pogrom against Jews in the history of [[Muntenia]]. Following the rebellion, Sima escaped to [[Nazi Germany|Germany]], and later to [[Francoist Spain|Spain]], where he lived until his death.\n\n==In Romania==\nSima was born on 3 July 1907<ref>{{Cite book|title=Hitler's Forgotten Ally: Ion Antonescu and his Regime|last=Deletant|first=Dennis|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2006|isbn=978-1403993410|location=|pages=37|url-status=live}}</ref> near [[F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219]], in [[Transylvania]], at the time a part of [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ionic\u0103|first=Ion I.|date=1996|title=Dealu Mohului: ceremonia agrar\u0103 a cununii \u00een \u021aara Oltului|url=|journal=Editura Minerva|volume=|pages=xi|via=}}</ref> Between 1926 and 1932 he studied at the Faculty of Letters and Philosophy of the [[University of Bucharest]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Searching for Cioran|last=Zarifopol-Johnston|first=Ilinca|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=253}}</ref> serving as councillor of the National Union of Christian Students of Romania.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=42|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Beginning in 1932 he began to work as a high-school teacher<ref>{{Cite book|title=The European Right|last=Rogger|first=Hans|publisher=University of California Press|year=1965|isbn=|location=|pages=555}}</ref> of [[logic]], [[Latin]], and [[philosophy]] in [[Caransebe\u0219|Caransenbe\u0219]], later transferring to a school in [[Lugoj]],<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=43|oclc=630496676}}</ref> and finally to [[Timi\u0219oara]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA%2C%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%201_0017.pdf|title=Horia Sima Vol. 1_0017|last=|first=|date=|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn October 1927, when a student, he joined the newly formed Iron Guard and became responsible for the [[Banat]] area. In the early 1930s, Sima participated in the legion's \"Excursions among the People\", wherein Iron Guard members would promote their movement in rural areas among peasants,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mann |first1=Michael |title=Fascists |date=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Los Angeles |isbn=978-0-511-21651-0 |page=280}}</ref> and had become a leading organizer for the Legion in [[Severin County]] by the 1930s.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=219|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> In 1935 he was promoted to the position of legionary commander of the Timi\u0219oara region.<ref name=\":11\" /> Sima became commander of the Iron Guard in late 1938 after its founder and leader, [[Corneliu Zelea Codreanu]], was imprisoned and later murdered. The Iron Guard had initially formed an interim leadership including Sima, Ion Belgae, Iordache Nicoara, Ion Antoniu, and Radu Mironovici in April 1938, but by August Sima remained the only leader not imprisoned by the Romanian government, eventually allowing him to bypass the hierarchy of leadership previously established and become leader of the Iron Guard.<ref name=\":8\" /> Tension had built both within the organization and country-wide following a series of assassinations of Iron Guard members, including Codreanu (who was killed by order of [[Carol II of Romania|King Carol II]]).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Europe: A History|last=Davies|first=Norman|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1996|isbn=0-19-820171-0|location=Oxford|pages=[https://archive.org/details/europehistory00davi_0/page/968 968]|url-status=live|url=https://archive.org/details/europehistory00davi_0/page/968}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Romanians: A History|last=Georgescu|first=Vlad|publisher=Ohio State University Press|year=1991|isbn=0-8142-0511-9|location=Columbus|pages=209\u2013210|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn early 1939, Sima fled to [[Nazi Germany]] through [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=86|oclc=630496676}}</ref> wherein he and a number of Romanian exiles attempted to plan a coup in early 1939; this plot was discovered by German police and a number of legionnaires were arrested.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth: Fascist Activism in Interwar Romania|last=Clark|first=Roland|publisher=Cornell University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=Ithaca|pages=221}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=221|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> In the summer of the same year, he was sent back to prepare and conduct [[Assassination of Armand C\u0103linescu|the assassination]] of the Romanian Prime Minister, [[Armand C\u0103linescu]], on 21 September 1939 - following his murder, a group of Legionnaires led by Sima assumed control of Romania's national radio broadcaster.<ref name=\":9\" /> After a power struggle for Legionary leadership between Sima and the group led by [[Vasile Noveanu]] that had formed while in exile, Sima was brought in by the short-lived [[Gheorghe T\u0103t\u0103rescu]] government to serve as state secretary within the Ministry of Education. He occupied this position for only six days, and the T\u0103t\u0103rescu government resigned on 3 July.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=141\u2013143|oclc=630496676}}</ref> On 4 July 1940, he joined the cabinet of Ion Gigurtu as the undersecretary of state in the Ministry of Public Education, as well as Minister of Religion and Arts,<ref name=\":1\" /> alongside two other Iron Guard members.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=222|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> Even though Sima resigned from the Gigurtu cabinet after only four days, antisemitism soon became codified in Romanian law, and by August 9, 1940, marriage between ethnic Romanians and Jews was prohibited, as was access to public education for Jewish individuals.<ref name=\":1\" /> Following [[Second Vienna Award|the secession of Northern Transylvania to Hungary]] on August 30, 1940, the Gigurtu government collapsed.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nBeginning in August 1940, the Iron Guard faction controlled by Horia Sima began to organize for a coup against King Carol II in reaction to the concession of Northern Transylvania. Sima, alongside Nicolae Petra\u0219cu, attempted to organize and arm groups of Legionnaires but managed to only gather about 1000 members willing to sacrifice themselves. On the occasion of the Second Vienna Award, Sima visited German authorities in an attempt to form an Axis-allied nationalist government, but left without success. By September he had prepared a manifesto for distribution and had set the date of the coup to 3 September.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=156\u2013157|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Due to a lack of manpower (only 500 of the intended 1000 Legionnaires participated in the coup) the coup was not carried out as planned - Legionnaires and police officers exchanged gunfire and clashed in centres such as [[Bra\u0219ov]], [[Constan\u021ba]] and Bucharest, and by the end of the day most Legionnaires had surrendered. Although the coup was unsuccessful, it spurred a number of protests against Carol II, and by 4 September the King had appointed General Ion Antonescu to the position of Prime Minister, thus halting the uprising.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=158\u2013161|oclc=630496676}}</ref>\n\n==National Legionary State==\n\n[[File: AntonescuYHoriaSimaOctubre1940.jpeg |thumb|Ion Antonescu and Horia Sima in October 1940]]\n\nIn September 1940, Carol II abdicated and the Iron Guard entered a tense political alliance with General [[Ion Antonescu]], commonly known as the [[National Legionary State]]. At that point, Sima was able to officially return from exile and rise to power as deputy prime minister in the new government and resume his activities as leader of the Iron Guard in Romania. Sima appointed five Legionnaires into ministerial positions within the National Legionary State, and Legionnaires assumed leadership roles as prefects in each of Romania's administrative districts.<ref name=\":10\" /> Romanian territorial cessions in the summer of 1940, secretly implemented by his [[Nazism|Nazi]] protectors, offered him the pretext for sparking a wave of [[Xenophobia|xenophobic]] and [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]] attacks. As a member of the government, Sima immediately initiated a series of brutal [[pogrom]]s, assassinations and de-possessions among [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jews]] and competing politicians.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=223|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref>\n\nSocial tension and issues began to arise in Romania under the Sima-Antonescu partnership, and Antonescu became increasingly frustrated with the Iron Guard, telling Sima that it was now \"...time for order and legality\" and that Legionnaires would \"not [be] allowed to demand audiences with the Ministers whenever they want.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=227|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> Additionally, Sima had failed to win the total support of his German allies, who feared that the Legionnaires were unprepared to administer the country effectively.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=166|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Infrastructure in Bucharest began to fail, and following a November earthquake, a number of deaths and the destruction of buildings in the capital further exposed the government's disorganization. By the end of 1940, prices fluctuated greatly and crops began to fail, producing 70% less food than the year prior. Frustration from citizens and Legionnaires fell on Sima, and Ion Zelea Codreanu, Corneliu Codreanu's father, referred to Sima as \"a Satan, in whom the soul of [[Mihai Stelescu|Stelescu]] lives\" (referencing the dissident Legionnaire Mihai Stelescu, who was said to have plotted to assassinate Corneliu Codreanu).<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Anii treizeci : extrema dreapt\u0103 rom\u00e2neasc\u0103|last=Ornea, Zigu, 1930-2001.|date=1996|publisher=Editura Funda\u0163iei Culturale Rom\u00e2ne|isbn=9735770660|location=|pages=306|oclc=895624740}}</ref> Sima responded to dissent within the Iron Guard by placing a number of prominent Legionnaires under house arrest, including Corneliu Zelea Codreanu's brothers and father.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=175\u2013176|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Alongside a group of dissatisfied Legionnaires, the senior Codreanu occupied the Iron Guard's Bucharest headquarters, the Casa Verde, and attempted a putsch. A number of Legionnaires also called for Sima's assassination. A movement within the Iron Guard soon arose to clear the late Corneliu Zelea Codreanu of his treason charges, and his body was exhumed.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=228|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref>\n\nBoth Horia Sima and Ion Antonescu were invited by the German government to [[Obersalzberg]] to meet with [[Adolf Hitler]] in order to mediate relations between the two Romanian leaders and to discuss German-Romanian relations. Sima refused to attend the meeting, citing both apprehension with the flight and that he felt it improper for both leaders to leave the country. Thus, Antonescu met with Hitler alone on January 14, 1941. By 17 January, encouraged by Hitler, relations between Antonescu and Sima ceased to exist, and the General had published an open letter denouncing Sima and accusing him of maintaining an \"anti-national attitude\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=179\u2013180|oclc=630496676}}</ref>  \n\nIn January 1941, the Iron Guard, increasingly dissatisfied with their suppression by Antonescu, staged a three-day rebellion, commonly known as the [[Legionnaires' rebellion and Bucharest pogrom|Legionnaire's Rebellion]]. Antonescu made [[Adolf Hitler]] choose between the military wing of the Romanian government and the Iron Guard. When Hitler decided to back him over the Guard, Antonescu proceeded with the suppression of the Legion.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Paxton |first1=Robert O. |title=The Anatomy of Fascism |date=2004 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |isbn=1-4000-4094-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/anatomyoffascism00paxt_0/page/97 97] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/anatomyoffascism00paxt_0/page/97 }}</ref> In the Bucharest pogrom, which grew from this power struggle, Iron Guardists destroyed synagogues, vandalized and ransacked Jewish homes and stores,<ref>{{Citation|title=Holocaust Survivor Baruch Cohen - the Bucharest Pogrom|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK0AqZzIUcM|language=en|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> and killed and tortured 121 Jews (as well as an additional 30 in smaller towns, specifically in [[Ploie\u015fti]] and [[Constan\u021ba|Constan\u0163a]]).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vago|first=Bela Adalbert|date=2007|title=Iron Guard|url=http://www.jevzajcg.me/enciklopedia/Encyclopaedia%20Judaica,%20v.%2010%20(Inz-Iz).pdf|journal=Encyclopedia Judaica|volume=10|pages=29|isbn=978-0-02-865938-1|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Romania|title=Romania|last=Volovici|first=Leon|date=19 November 2010|website=YIVO|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> In addition to widespread torture and rape of Jews, the Legionary movement was responsible for the mock ''[[shechita]]'' of five Jews, including a five-year-old girl, who had their stomachs cut open, entrails removed, and were hung from meat hooks and labelled \"[[Kashrut|Kosher]]\" in a Bucharest slaughterhouse.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Toldot ha-Sho\u02bcah : Romanyah|last=Ancel, Jean.|last2=\u05d0\u05e0\u05e6\u05f3\u05dc, \u05d6\u05f3\u05d0\u05df.|date=2002|publisher=Yad \u1e7fa-shem|isbn=9653081578|location=Yerushalayim|pages=363\u2013400|oclc=52610317}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ushmm.org/research/center/presentations/features/details/2005-03-10/|title=Romania Facing its Past|last=|first=|date=2011-12-29|website=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229225552/http://www.ushmm.org/research/center/presentations/features/details/2005-03-10/|archive-date=2011-12-29|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref> According to the American minister to Romania, Franklin Mitt Gunther, \"Sixty Jewish corpses were discovered on the hooks used for carcasses. They were all skinned... and the quantity of blood about was evidence that they had been skinned alive\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Blowback|last=Simpson|first=Christopher|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|year=1988|isbn=|location=New York|pages=255}}</ref>\n\n==Exile==\nUnlike most Legionnaires, who were imprisoned by Antonescu following the suppression of the coup attempt, Sima escaped imprisonment. Being housed first at the [[Sicherheitsdienst]] headquarters in Bucharest, Sima was evacuated on January 23rd and hidden in the home of the Gestapo representative to Romania, but soon moved to his sister's residence in Bucharest. Soon after he was again moved by the Sicherheitsdienst to Bra\u0219ov, and finally to Sibiu, disguised as an [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] officer.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=184\u2013186|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Sima, alongside a number of other hidden Legionnaires, was able to leave Romania for Germany, where they were placed under strict supervision at a villa in [[Berkenbr\u00fcck]]. Meanwhile, Romanian authorities sentenced him (on 16 June 1941) to 12 years hard labour ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]''<ref>Zamfirescu, Drago\u0219: Legiunea Arhanghelul Mihail, Editura Enciclopedic\u0103, Bucure\u0219ti, 1997.</ref> to ensure his permanent exile.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1942, he escaped and fled to [[Italy]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA%2C%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%201_0018.pdf|title=Horia Sima Vol. 1_0018|last=|first=|date=|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref> but was soon extradited back to Germany on the orders of [[Galeazzo Ciano]]. In his political journal, on 26 December 1942, Ciano wrote that, \"Since [Sima] got out of Germany with a false passport, [[Heinrich Himmler|Himmler]] demands his extradition. For my part, I advised [[Benito Mussolini|the Duce]] to grant his extradition forthwith, especially since his presence here would create friction with Antonescu. And then, all things considered, there will be one less crook.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/GibsonHughTheCianoDiaries19391943TheCompleteUnabridgedDiariesOfCountGaleazzoCian/Gibson%2C+Hugh+-+The+Ciano+Diaries+1939-1943+The+Complete%2C+Unabridged+Diaries+of+Count+Galeazzo+Ciano%2C+Italian+Minister+of+Foreign+Affairs%2C+1936-1943_djvu.txt|title=The Ciano diaries, 1939-1943 the complete, unabridged diaries of Count Galeazzo Ciano, Italian Minister for Foreign Affairs, 1936-1943.|last=Galeazzo|first=Ciano|date=1973|publisher=H. Fertig|isbn=|location=|pages=|oclc=768195195|url-status=live}}</ref> After travelling to Italy, thus disobeying a contract signed with Germany meant to limit the political activities of the exiled Legionnaires,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=236\u2013238|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Sima and the others exiled were imprisoned in a special, humane section of the [[Buchenwald concentration camp]] specifically meant for Iron Guard members.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=255\u2013256|oclc=630496676}}</ref> By October 1943, Sima had been sentenced again, this time to a lifetime of hard labour, a fine of 10,000 [[Romanian leu|lei]], and five years of correctional imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=199|oclc=630496676}}</ref>\n\nWhile interned at Buchenwald, Sima was faced with the dissent of several groups of Legionnaires, who distanced themselves from his policies, stating that they did not approve of the way in which he had run the country and the movement, and were starting to appeal to the German supervisors for distinctions to be made in their case. [[:ro:Constantin_Papanace|Constantin Papanace]], a leading Legionary figure who had served as the secretary of the State Department of Finance under the National Legionary State,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/519697ec993294098d50cd5a|title=Constantin Papanace 0007 - Nazi War Crimes Disclosure Act|last=|first=|date=1949|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> would later describe Sima as a \"terrorist\", noting that he \"[took] advantage of and abused... his connections\", and that Sima possessed \"non-discipline... a dangerous dilettantism, not to mention infantilism.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Evolutia Misc\u0103rii Legionare dup\u0103 arestarea si asasinarea C\u0103pitanului - Cazul Horia Sima|last=Papanace|first=Constantin|publisher=Editura Armatolii|year=1977|isbn=|location=Rome|pages=8}}</ref> Legionnaires increasingly began to blame Sima's leadership of the Iron Guard for the death of Codreanu, citing his previous actions as commander in 1938 as \"terroristic\" and \"tumultuous\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=Dreapta politica romaneasca. Politica si ideologie: 1919-1941|last=Ciucanu|first=Corneliu|publisher=Editura Mica Valahie|year=2009|isbn=|location=Bucharest|pages=35}}</ref> It was to enforce the split which is still present in the political legacy of the Iron Guard. By 1943, the Iron Guard - now in exile in [[Rostock]], Germany - had split into at least three distinct groups with separate leadership, not including the Legionnaires who considered Sima their legitimate leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0018|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0018 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sima was transferred to [[Oranienburg concentration camp|Oranienburg]] in April 1943.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=258|oclc=630496676}}</ref>\n\nWhen Romania changed sides in [[World War II]], joining the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in August 1944, Sima was released and instructed to create a pro-Nazi puppet government-in-exile in [[Vienna]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA%2C%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%201_0062.pdf|title=Horia Sima Vol. 1_0062|last=|first=|date=19 July 1945|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref> and would broadcast instructions to fascist battalions via German radio.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Who Was Who in Twentieth Century Romania|last=Ionescu|first=\u015eerban N.|publisher=East European Monographs, Columbia University Press|year=1994|isbn=978-0880332927|location=New York|pages=266\u2013267|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA%2C%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%201_0123.pdf|title=Horia Sima Vol. 1_0123|last=|first=|date=10 November 1950|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref> As the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] offensive proved unstoppable, he fled to [[Altaussee]] under the alias ''Josef Weber''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=2003|title=Guvernul National Roman de la Viena|url=|journal=Anuarul Institutului de Istorie \"A.D. Xenopol.\"|publisher=Editura Academiei Rom\u00e2ne|volume=38|page=165|via=}}</ref> Living in [[Paris]], in Italy, and finally in [[Francoist Spain|Spain]], he was sentenced to death in Romania in 1946.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tudor |first1=Lucian |title=The Romanian Iron Guard: Its Origins, History and Legacy |journal=The Occidental Quarterly |date=2014 |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=99\u2013100 |url=https://www.academia.edu/7695200}}</ref> \n\nDuring his exile, the question of leadership within the Iron Guard was still a salient issue, and the now-disjointed organization was fraught with infighting and factionalism. In January 1954, Sima was formally and publicly \"disowned\" by the Legionnaire movement through a 13-page document published in ''Vastra'' magazine after controversy arose regarding aspects of his private life over the alleged existence of an illegitimate child <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/DosarulRusiniiAdulterulLuiHoriaSimaFeb.1954/page/n1|title=Dosarul Rusinii Adulterul Lui Horia Sima|last=|first=|date=February 1954|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/CIA-RDP80-00810A003900930009-8|title=Renunciation of Horia Sima by the Iron Guard - Cental Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=12 April 1954|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0010|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0010 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />: on 6 November 1948, Mardarie Popinciuc, a Romanian living in exile in Argentina,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=x8NWAgAAQBAJ|title=Romanians in Canada|last=Bujea|first=Eleanor|publisher=|year=2009|isbn=9781929200146|location=|pages=189}}</ref> forwarded a letter to Legionary leaders alleging that Sima had illegitimately fathered the child of a fellow Legionnaire identified only as \"B\" while in France,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0011|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0011 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=5 September 1955|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a claim supported by the mother of the child and a number of other Legionnaires.<ref name=\":4\" /> This allegation caused the resignation of a number of members of the Guard, as well as the foundation of a new faction named \"Mo\u0163a-Marin\" under the leadership of Ovidiu G\u0103in\u0103.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to [[Central Intelligence Agency]] documents, Sima, in light of these allegations, had originally planned to end his career by parachuting into Romania,<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> where he had previously been sentenced to death following two separate trials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/Microsoft%20Word%20-%206024.pdf|title=Horia Sima|last=|first=|date=|website=Yad Vashem|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref> In addition to this split and the formation of the \"Mo\u0163a-Marin\" group, there also existed controversies surrounding Sima's politics and policies: a split of \"progressive\" Guardists denounced Sima's leadership as \"reactionary\" and \"doomed to failure\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0003|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0003 - Cental Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=1 July 1950|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and a further number of distinct splinter groups with conflicting ideologies, tactics, and leadership formed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0054|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0054 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=8 May 1945|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0005|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0005 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/519697ec993294098d50cd83|title=Constantin Papanace 0048 - Nazi War Crimes Disclosure Act|last=|first=|date=18 August 1951|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nUntil the 1990s, Sima attempted to form connections with mainstream ideologies of [[anti-Communism]], insisting on the Guard's allegiance to the [[Free World]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=241|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> The party oriented itself towards denunciations of [[Communist Romania]], and Sima continued to publish ideological literature in exile in Spain, including a monthly newsletter titled \"Tara si Exilul\" (\"The Country and Exile\"), which found readership in Israel, Australia, Germany, and the United States.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA,%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%202_0083.pdf|title=Horia Sima, vol. 2_0083|last=|first=|date=17 November 1975|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This adoption of a new image was, in part, successful - beginning in 1949, the United States helped to fund [[NATO]] missions to parachute Iron Guard members into Romania in an attempt to undermine the socialist government.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=242|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> After the death of his wife Elvira in 1974, Sima resided with fellow exiled Iron Guard member Georghe Costa in [[Madrid]], and the two used funds from publishing and donations as income.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nSima reportedly died in Madrid on 25 May 1993, aged 85, and was buried alongside his wife Elvira Sima at [[Torredembarra]], near [[Barcelona]], Spain, although some sources cite his place of death as [[Augsburg]], Germany.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.bjt.ro/bv/ScritoriBanateni/VALENAS_Liviu/Valenasmiscarea.pdf|title=Mi\u015fcarea Legionari\u0103 - \u00centre Adev\u0103r \u015fi Mistificare|last=V\u0103lena\u015f|first=Liviu|publisher=Editura Marineasa|year=2000|isbn=|location=Timi\u0219oara|pages=171|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''[http://miscarea.com/horia-sima-english.htm Europe at the crossroads: war or capitulation?]''; [[Munich]] Verlag \"Vestitori\", 1955\n* ''The Rumanian situation after 19 years of Communist slavery and policies of the western powers, 1944-1963; a declaration by the Rumanian Legionary Movement;'' [[Rio de Janeiro]]?, 1963?\n* ''[http://miscarea.com/horia-sima-english1.htm Hunger In Romania];'' 1964\n* ''Articole politice, 1950-1963''; 1967\n* ''XLth anniversary of the foundation of the Rumanian legionary movement, 1927-1967; declarations of the legionary movement concerning the fate of the free world and the tragedy of the Rumanian people''; 1968\n* ''Ce este comunismul?''; Madrid, Editura Dacia, 1972\n* ''Histoire du Mouvement L\u00e9gionnaire''; Rio de Janeiro, 1972 (''The History of the Legionary Movement'', Legionary Press, 1995)\n* ''An interview with Horia Sima, Commander-in-chief, Legion of the Archangel Michael''; \"Thule of Palermo\", 1977\n* ''The Truth About The Legionary Movement''\n* ''The Natural World Order''\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*''Romanian Nationalism: The Legionary Movement'' by Alexander E. Ronnett  {{ISBN|0-8294-0232-2}} Chicago: Loyola University Press, 1995.\n*''The Green Shirts and the Others: A History of Fascism in Hungary and Rumania'' by [[Nicholas M. Nagy-Talavera]], 1970 {{ISBN|973-9432-11-5}} & {{ISBN|0-8179-1851-5}}\n*''[[Biographical Dictionary of the Extreme Right Since 1890]]'' edited by [[Philip Rees]], 1991, {{ISBN|0-13-089301-3}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020620015619/http://hist.academic.claremontmckenna.edu/jpetropoulos/ironguard/leaders.htm Leadership of the Iron Guard]\n* [http://www.axishistory.com/index.php?id=2353 Romanian volunteers in the Waffen-SS] by Marc Rikmenspoel\n\n*{{PM20|FID=pe/016573}}\n{{Gigurtu Cabinet}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sima, Horia}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219]]\n[[Category:Members of the Iron Guard]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Culture]]\n[[Category:World War II political leaders]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian collaborators with Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Romanian fascists]]\n[[Category:Romanian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Romanian Austro-Hungarians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Romanian Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Christian fascists]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian emigrants to Spain]]\n[[Category:People sentenced to death in absentia]]\n[[Category:Romanian prisoners sentenced to death]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to death by Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Romanian nationalists]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Romania]]\n[[Category:Anti-Masonry]]\n[[Category:Fascist rulers]]\n[[Category:Fascist politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Romanian|Horia Sima|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Horia Sima\n| honorific-prefix = \n| image = Horia Sima.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| order = [[Conduc\u0103tor|Co-Conducator]] of Romania\n| term_start = 14 September 1940\n| alongside = [[Ion Antonescu]]&nbsp;\n| term_end = 14 February 1941\n| predecessor = [[Carol II of Romania|Carol II]] (''as [[King of Romania]]'')\n| successor = Ion Antonescu (''as sole Conduc\u0103tor'')\n| vicepresident = \n| deputy = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1907|07|03}}\n| birth_place = [[F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219]], [[Lands of the Crown of Saint Stephen|Transleithania]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1993|05|25|1907|07|03}}\n| death_place = [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n| death_cause = \n| constituency = \n| nationality = [[Romania|Romanian]]\n| party = [[Iron Guard]]\n| spouse = \n| profession = \n| religion = [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]]\n}}\n{{Fascism in Romania}}\n'''Horia Sima''' (3 July 1907 &ndash; 25 May 1993) was a [[Romania|Romanian]] [[fascist]] politician, best known as the second and last leader of the fascist paramilitary movement known as the [[Iron Guard]], also known as the Legionnaire Movement. Sima was also the vice president of the council of ministers in [[Ion Antonescu]]'s [[National Legionary State]], and a short-lived minister in the government of [[Ion Gigurtu]]. In January 1941, Sima initiated and led the [[Legionnaires' rebellion and Bucharest pogrom|Legionnaires' Rebellion]] against [[Conduc\u0103tor]] Ion Antonescu and the Romanian Army, for which he was sentenced to death, as well as the [[Legionnaires' rebellion and Bucharest pogrom|Bucharest pogrom]], the largest and most violent pogrom against Jews in the history of [[Muntenia]]. Following the rebellion, Sima escaped to [[Nazi Germany|Germany]], and later to [[Francoist Spain|Spain]], where he lived until his death.\n\n==In Romania==\nSima was born on 3 July 1907<ref>{{Cite book|title=Hitler's Forgotten Ally: Ion Antonescu and his Regime|last=Deletant|first=Dennis|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2006|isbn=978-1403993410|location=|pages=37|url-status=live}}</ref> near [[F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219]], in [[Transylvania]], at the time a part of [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ionic\u0103|first=Ion I.|date=1996|title=Dealu Mohului: ceremonia agrar\u0103 a cununii \u00een \u021aara Oltului|url=|journal=Editura Minerva|volume=|pages=xi|via=}}</ref> Between 1926 and 1932 he studied at the Faculty of Letters and Philosophy of the [[University of Bucharest]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Searching for Cioran|last=Zarifopol-Johnston|first=Ilinca|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=253}}</ref> serving as councillor of the National Union of Christian Students of Romania.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=42|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Beginning in 1932 he began to work as a high-school teacher<ref>{{Cite book|title=The European Right|last=Rogger|first=Hans|publisher=University of California Press|year=1965|isbn=|location=|pages=555}}</ref> of [[logic]], [[Latin]], and [[philosophy]] in [[Caransebe\u0219|Caransenbe\u0219]], later transferring to a school in [[Lugoj]],<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=43|oclc=630496676}}</ref> and finally to [[Timi\u0219oara]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA%2C%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%201_0017.pdf|title=Horia Sima Vol. 1_0017|last=|first=|date=|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn October 1927, when a student, he joined the newly formed Iron Guard and became responsible for the [[Banat]] area. In the early 1930s, Sima participated in the legion's \"Excursions among the People\", wherein Iron Guard members would promote their movement in rural areas among peasants,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mann |first1=Michael |title=Fascists |date=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Los Angeles |isbn=978-0-511-21651-0 |page=280}}</ref> and had become a leading organizer for the Legion in [[Severin County]] by the 1930s.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=219|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> In 1935 he was promoted to the position of legionary commander of the Timi\u0219oara region.<ref name=\":11\" /> Sima became commander of the Iron Guard in late 1938 after its founder and leader, [[Corneliu Zelea Codreanu]], was imprisoned and later murdered. The Iron Guard had initially formed an interim leadership including Sima, Ion Belgae, Iordache Nicoara, Ion Antoniu, and Radu Mironovici in April 1938, but by August Sima remained the only leader not imprisoned by the Romanian government, eventually allowing him to bypass the hierarchy of leadership previously established and become leader of the Iron Guard.<ref name=\":8\" /> Tension had built both within the organization and country-wide following a series of assassinations of Iron Guard members, including Codreanu (who was killed by order of [[Carol II of Romania|King Carol II]]).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Europe: A History|last=Davies|first=Norman|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1996|isbn=0-19-820171-0|location=Oxford|pages=[https://archive.org/details/europehistory00davi_0/page/968 968]|url-status=live|url=https://archive.org/details/europehistory00davi_0/page/968}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Romanians: A History|last=Georgescu|first=Vlad|publisher=Ohio State University Press|year=1991|isbn=0-8142-0511-9|location=Columbus|pages=209\u2013210|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn early 1939, Sima fled to [[Nazi Germany]] through [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=86|oclc=630496676}}</ref> wherein he and a number of Romanian exiles attempted to plan a coup in early 1939; this plot was discovered by German police and a number of legionnaires were arrested.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth: Fascist Activism in Interwar Romania|last=Clark|first=Roland|publisher=Cornell University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=Ithaca|pages=221}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=221|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> In the summer of the same year, he was sent back to prepare and conduct [[Assassination of Armand C\u0103linescu|the assassination]] of the Romanian Prime Minister, [[Armand C\u0103linescu]], on 21 September 1939 - following his murder, a group of Legionnaires led by Sima assumed control of Romania's national radio broadcaster.<ref name=\":9\" /> After a power struggle for Legionary leadership between Sima and the group led by [[Vasile Noveanu]] that had formed while in exile, Sima was brought in by the short-lived [[Gheorghe T\u0103t\u0103rescu]] government to serve as state secretary within the Ministry of Education. He occupied this position for only six days, and the T\u0103t\u0103rescu government resigned on 3 July.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=141\u2013143|oclc=630496676}}</ref> On 4 July 1940, he joined the cabinet of Ion Gigurtu as the undersecretary of state in the Ministry of Public Education, as well as Minister of Religion and Arts,<ref name=\":1\" /> alongside two other Iron Guard members.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=222|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> Even though Sima resigned from the Gigurtu cabinet after only four days, antisemitism soon became codified in Romanian law, and by August 9, 1940, marriage between ethnic Romanians and Jews was prohibited, as was access to public education for Jewish individuals.<ref name=\":1\" /> Following [[Second Vienna Award|the secession of Northern Transylvania to Hungary]] on August 30, 1940, the Gigurtu government collapsed.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nBeginning in August 1940, the Iron Guard faction controlled by Horia Sima began to organize for a coup against King Carol II in reaction to the concession of Northern Transylvania. Sima, alongside Nicolae Petra\u0219cu, attempted to organize and arm groups of Legionnaires but managed to only gather about 1000 members willing to sacrifice themselves. On the occasion of the Second Vienna Award, Sima visited German authorities in an attempt to form an Axis-allied nationalist government, but left without success. By September he had prepared a manifesto for distribution and had set the date of the coup to 3 September.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=156\u2013157|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Due to a lack of manpower (only 500 of the intended 1000 Legionnaires participated in the coup) the coup was not carried out as planned - Legionnaires and police officers exchanged gunfire and clashed in centres such as [[Bra\u0219ov]], [[Constan\u021ba]] and Bucharest, and by the end of the day most Legionnaires had surrendered. Although the coup was unsuccessful, it spurred a number of protests against Carol II, and by 4 September the King had appointed General Ion Antonescu to the position of Prime Minister, thus halting the uprising.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=158\u2013161|oclc=630496676}}</ref>\n\n==National Legionary State==\n\n[[File: AntonescuYHoriaSimaOctubre1940.jpeg |thumb|Ion Antonescu and Horia Sima in October 1940]]\n\nIn September 1940, Carol II abdicated and the Iron Guard entered a tense political alliance with General [[Ion Antonescu]], commonly known as the [[National Legionary State]]. At that point, Sima was able to officially return from exile and rise to power as deputy prime minister in the new government and resume his activities as leader of the Iron Guard in Romania. Sima appointed five Legionnaires into ministerial positions within the National Legionary State, and Legionnaires assumed leadership roles as prefects in each of Romania's administrative districts.<ref name=\":10\" /> Romanian territorial cessions in the summer of 1940, secretly implemented by his [[Nazism|Nazi]] protectors, offered him the pretext for sparking a wave of [[Xenophobia|xenophobic]] and [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]] attacks. As a member of the government, Sima immediately initiated a series of brutal [[pogrom]]s, assassinations and de-possessions among [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jews]] and competing politicians.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=223|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref>\n\nSocial tension and issues began to arise in Romania under the Sima-Antonescu partnership, and Antonescu became increasingly frustrated with the Iron Guard, telling Sima that it was now \"...time for order and legality\" and that Legionnaires would \"not [be] allowed to demand audiences with the Ministers whenever they want.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=227|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> Additionally, Sima had failed to win the total support of his German allies, who feared that the Legionnaires were unprepared to administer the country effectively.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=166|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Infrastructure in Bucharest began to fail, and following a November earthquake, a number of deaths and the destruction of buildings in the capital further exposed the government's disorganization. By the end of 1940, prices fluctuated greatly and crops began to fail, producing 70% less food than the year prior. Frustration from citizens and Legionnaires fell on Sima, and Ion Zelea Codreanu, Corneliu Codreanu's father, referred to Sima as \"a Satan, in whom the soul of [[Mihai Stelescu|Stelescu]] lives\" (referencing the dissident Legionnaire Mihai Stelescu, who was said to have plotted to assassinate Corneliu Codreanu).<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Anii treizeci : extrema dreapt\u0103 rom\u00e2neasc\u0103|last=Ornea, Zigu, 1930-2001.|date=1996|publisher=Editura Funda\u0163iei Culturale Rom\u00e2ne|isbn=9735770660|location=|pages=306|oclc=895624740}}</ref> Sima responded to dissent within the Iron Guard by placing a number of prominent Legionnaires under house arrest, including Corneliu Zelea Codreanu's brothers and father.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=175\u2013176|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Alongside a group of dissatisfied Legionnaires, the senior Codreanu occupied the Iron Guard's Bucharest headquarters, the Casa Verde, and attempted a putsch. A number of Legionnaires also called for Sima's assassination. A movement within the Iron Guard soon arose to clear the late Corneliu Zelea Codreanu of his treason charges, and his body was exhumed.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=228|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref>\n\nBoth Horia Sima and Ion Antonescu were invited by the German government to [[Obersalzberg]] to meet with [[Adolf Hitler]] in order to mediate relations between the two Romanian leaders and to discuss German-Romanian relations. Sima refused to attend the meeting, citing both apprehension with the flight and that he felt it improper for both leaders to leave the country. Thus, Antonescu met with Hitler alone on January 14, 1941. By 17 January, encouraged by Hitler, relations between Antonescu and Sima ceased to exist, and the General had published an open letter denouncing Sima and accusing him of maintaining an \"anti-national attitude\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=179\u2013180|oclc=630496676}}</ref>  \n\nIn January 1941, the Iron Guard, increasingly dissatisfied with their suppression by Antonescu, staged a three-day rebellion, commonly known as the [[Legionnaires' rebellion and Bucharest pogrom|Legionnaire's Rebellion]]. Antonescu made [[Adolf Hitler]] choose between the military wing of the Romanian government and the Iron Guard. When Hitler decided to back him over the Guard, Antonescu proceeded with the suppression of the Legion.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Paxton |first1=Robert O. |title=The Anatomy of Fascism |date=2004 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |isbn=1-4000-4094-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/anatomyoffascism00paxt_0/page/97 97] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/anatomyoffascism00paxt_0/page/97 }}</ref> In the Bucharest pogrom, which grew from this power struggle, Iron Guardists destroyed synagogues, vandalized and ransacked Jewish homes and stores,<ref>{{Citation|title=Holocaust Survivor Baruch Cohen - the Bucharest Pogrom|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK0AqZzIUcM|language=en|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> and killed and tortured 121 Jews (as well as an additional 30 in smaller towns, specifically in [[Ploie\u015fti]] and [[Constan\u021ba|Constan\u0163a]]).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vago|first=Bela Adalbert|date=2007|title=Iron Guard|url=http://www.jevzajcg.me/enciklopedia/Encyclopaedia%20Judaica,%20v.%2010%20(Inz-Iz).pdf|journal=Encyclopedia Judaica|volume=10|pages=29|isbn=978-0-02-865938-1|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Romania|title=Romania|last=Volovici|first=Leon|date=19 November 2010|website=YIVO|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> In addition to widespread torture and rape of Jews, the Legionary movement was responsible for the mock ''[[shechita]]'' of five Jews, including a five-year-old girl, who had their stomachs cut open, entrails removed, and were hung from meat hooks and labelled \"[[Kashrut|Kosher]]\" in a Bucharest slaughterhouse.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Toldot ha-Sho\u02bcah : Romanyah|last=Ancel, Jean.|last2=\u05d0\u05e0\u05e6\u05f3\u05dc, \u05d6\u05f3\u05d0\u05df.|date=2002|publisher=Yad \u1e7fa-shem|isbn=9653081578|location=Yerushalayim|pages=363\u2013400|oclc=52610317}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ushmm.org/research/center/presentations/features/details/2005-03-10/|title=Romania Facing its Past|last=|first=|date=2011-12-29|website=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229225552/http://www.ushmm.org/research/center/presentations/features/details/2005-03-10/|archive-date=2011-12-29|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref> According to the American minister to Romania, Franklin Mitt Gunther, \"Sixty Jewish corpses were discovered on the hooks used for carcasses. They were all skinned... and the quantity of blood about was evidence that they had been skinned alive\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Blowback|last=Simpson|first=Christopher|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|year=1988|isbn=|location=New York|pages=255}}</ref>\n\n==Exile==\nUnlike most Legionnaires, who were imprisoned by Antonescu following the suppression of the coup attempt, Sima escaped imprisonment. Being housed first at the [[Sicherheitsdienst]] headquarters in Bucharest, Sima was evacuated on January 23rd and hidden in the home of the Gestapo representative to Romania, but soon moved to his sister's residence in Bucharest. Soon after he was again moved by the Sicherheitsdienst to Bra\u0219ov, and finally to Sibiu, disguised as an [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] officer.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=184\u2013186|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Sima, alongside a number of other hidden Legionnaires, was able to leave Romania for Germany, where they were placed under strict supervision at a villa in [[Berkenbr\u00fcck]]. Meanwhile, Romanian authorities sentenced him (on 16 June 1941) to 12 years hard labour ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]''<ref>Zamfirescu, Drago\u0219: Legiunea Arhanghelul Mihail, Editura Enciclopedic\u0103, Bucure\u0219ti, 1997.</ref> to ensure his permanent exile.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1942, he escaped and fled to [[Italy]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA%2C%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%201_0018.pdf|title=Horia Sima Vol. 1_0018|last=|first=|date=|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref> but was soon extradited back to Germany on the orders of [[Galeazzo Ciano]]. In his political journal, on 26 December 1942, Ciano wrote that, \"Since [Sima] got out of Germany with a false passport, [[Heinrich Himmler|Himmler]] demands his extradition. For my part, I advised [[Benito Mussolini|the Duce]] to grant his extradition forthwith, especially since his presence here would create friction with Antonescu. And then, all things considered, there will be one less crook.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/GibsonHughTheCianoDiaries19391943TheCompleteUnabridgedDiariesOfCountGaleazzoCian/Gibson%2C+Hugh+-+The+Ciano+Diaries+1939-1943+The+Complete%2C+Unabridged+Diaries+of+Count+Galeazzo+Ciano%2C+Italian+Minister+of+Foreign+Affairs%2C+1936-1943_djvu.txt|title=The Ciano diaries, 1939-1943 the complete, unabridged diaries of Count Galeazzo Ciano, Italian Minister for Foreign Affairs, 1936-1943.|last=Galeazzo|first=Ciano|date=1973|publisher=H. Fertig|isbn=|location=|pages=|oclc=768195195|url-status=live}}</ref> After travelling to Italy, thus disobeying a contract signed with Germany meant to limit the political activities of the exiled Legionnaires,<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=236\u2013238|oclc=630496676}}</ref> Sima and the others exiled were imprisoned in a special, humane section of the [[Buchenwald concentration camp]] specifically meant for Iron Guard members.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=255\u2013256|oclc=630496676}}</ref> By October 1943, Sima had been sentenced again, this time to a lifetime of hard labour, a fine of 10,000 [[Romanian leu|lei]], and five years of correctional imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=199|oclc=630496676}}</ref>\n\nWhile interned at Buchenwald, Sima was faced with the dissent of several groups of Legionnaires, who distanced themselves from his policies, stating that they did not approve of the way in which he had run the country and the movement, and were starting to appeal to the German supervisors for distinctions to be made in their case. [[:ro:Constantin_Papanace|Constantin Papanace]], a leading Legionary figure who had served as the secretary of the State Department of Finance under the National Legionary State,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/519697ec993294098d50cd5a|title=Constantin Papanace 0007 - Nazi War Crimes Disclosure Act|last=|first=|date=1949|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> would later describe Sima as a \"terrorist\", noting that he \"[took] advantage of and abused... his connections\", and that Sima possessed \"non-discipline... a dangerous dilettantism, not to mention infantilism.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Evolutia Misc\u0103rii Legionare dup\u0103 arestarea si asasinarea C\u0103pitanului - Cazul Horia Sima|last=Papanace|first=Constantin|publisher=Editura Armatolii|year=1977|isbn=|location=Rome|pages=8}}</ref> Legionnaires increasingly began to blame Sima's leadership of the Iron Guard for the death of Codreanu, citing his previous actions as commander in 1938 as \"terroristic\" and \"tumultuous\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=Dreapta politica romaneasca. Politica si ideologie: 1919-1941|last=Ciucanu|first=Corneliu|publisher=Editura Mica Valahie|year=2009|isbn=|location=Bucharest|pages=35}}</ref> It was to enforce the split which is still present in the political legacy of the Iron Guard. By 1943, the Iron Guard - now in exile in [[Rostock]], Germany - had split into at least three distinct groups with separate leadership, not including the Legionnaires who considered Sima their legitimate leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0018|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0018 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sima was transferred to [[Oranienburg concentration camp|Oranienburg]] in April 1943.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The legionary movement after Corneliu Codreanu : from the dictatorship of King Carol II to the communist regime (February 1938 - August 1944)|last=\u021aiu, Ilarion.|date=2010|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780880336598|location=|pages=258|oclc=630496676}}</ref>\n\nWhen Romania changed sides in [[World War II]], joining the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in August 1944, Sima was released and instructed to create a pro-Nazi puppet government-in-exile in [[Vienna]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA%2C%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%201_0062.pdf|title=Horia Sima Vol. 1_0062|last=|first=|date=19 July 1945|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref> and would broadcast instructions to fascist battalions via German radio.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Who Was Who in Twentieth Century Romania|last=Ionescu|first=\u015eerban N.|publisher=East European Monographs, Columbia University Press|year=1994|isbn=978-0880332927|location=New York|pages=266\u2013267|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA%2C%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%201_0123.pdf|title=Horia Sima Vol. 1_0123|last=|first=|date=10 November 1950|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref> As the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] offensive proved unstoppable, he fled to [[Altaussee]] under the alias ''Josef Weber''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=2003|title=Guvernul National Roman de la Viena|url=|journal=Anuarul Institutului de Istorie \"A.D. Xenopol.\"|publisher=Editura Academiei Rom\u00e2ne|volume=38|page=165|via=}}</ref> Living in [[Paris]], in Italy, and finally in [[Francoist Spain|Spain]], he was sentenced to death in Romania in 1946.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tudor |first1=Lucian |title=The Romanian Iron Guard: Its Origins, History and Legacy |journal=The Occidental Quarterly |date=2014 |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=99\u2013100 |url=https://www.academia.edu/7695200}}</ref> \n\nDuring his exile, the question of leadership within the Iron Guard was still a salient issue, and the now-disjointed organization was fraught with infighting and factionalism. In January 1954, Sima was formally and publicly \"disowned\" by the Legionnaire movement through a 13-page document published in ''Vastra'' magazine after controversy arose regarding aspects of his private life over the alleged existence of an illegitimate child <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/DosarulRusiniiAdulterulLuiHoriaSimaFeb.1954/page/n1|title=Dosarul Rusinii Adulterul Lui Horia Sima|last=|first=|date=February 1954|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/CIA-RDP80-00810A003900930009-8|title=Renunciation of Horia Sima by the Iron Guard - Cental Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=12 April 1954|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0010|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0010 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />: on 6 November 1948, Mardarie Popinciuc, a Romanian living in exile in Argentina,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=x8NWAgAAQBAJ|title=Romanians in Canada|last=Bujea|first=Eleanor|publisher=|year=2009|isbn=9781929200146|location=|pages=189}}</ref> forwarded a letter to Legionary leaders alleging that Sima had illegitimately fathered the child of a fellow Legionnaire identified only as \"B\" while in France,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0011|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0011 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=5 September 1955|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> a claim supported by the mother of the child and a number of other Legionnaires.<ref name=\":4\" /> This allegation caused the resignation of a number of members of the Guard, as well as the foundation of a new faction named \"Mo\u0163a-Marin\" under the leadership of Ovidiu G\u0103in\u0103.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to [[Central Intelligence Agency]] documents, Sima, in light of these allegations, had originally planned to end his career by parachuting into Romania,<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> where he had previously been sentenced to death following two separate trials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/Microsoft%20Word%20-%206024.pdf|title=Horia Sima|last=|first=|date=|website=Yad Vashem|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref> In addition to this split and the formation of the \"Mo\u0163a-Marin\" group, there also existed controversies surrounding Sima's politics and policies: a split of \"progressive\" Guardists denounced Sima's leadership as \"reactionary\" and \"doomed to failure\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0003|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0003 - Cental Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=1 July 1950|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and a further number of distinct splinter groups with conflicting ideologies, tactics, and leadership formed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0054|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0054 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=8 May 1945|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SIMAHORIAVOL1-0005|title=Sima, Horia Vol. 1_0005 - Central Intelligence Agency|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Archive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/519697ec993294098d50cd83|title=Constantin Papanace 0048 - Nazi War Crimes Disclosure Act|last=|first=|date=18 August 1951|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nUntil the 1990s, Sima attempted to form connections with mainstream ideologies of [[anti-Communism]], insisting on the Guard's allegiance to the [[Free World]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=241|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> The party oriented itself towards denunciations of [[Communist Romania]], and Sima continued to publish ideological literature in exile in Spain, including a monthly newsletter titled \"Tara si Exilul\" (\"The Country and Exile\"), which found readership in Israel, Australia, Germany, and the United States.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/SIMA,%20HORIA%20%20%20VOL.%202_0083.pdf|title=Horia Sima, vol. 2_0083|last=|first=|date=17 November 1975|website=Central Intelligence Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This adoption of a new image was, in part, successful - beginning in 1949, the United States helped to fund [[NATO]] missions to parachute Iron Guard members into Romania in an attempt to undermine the socialist government.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Legionary Youth|last=Clark|first=Roland|date=2015-06-05|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801456343|location=Ithaca, NY|pages=242|doi = 10.7591/9780801456343}}</ref> After the death of his wife Elvira in 1974, Sima resided with fellow exiled Iron Guard member Georghe Costa in [[Madrid]], and the two used funds from publishing and donations as income.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nSima reportedly died in Madrid on 25 May 1993, aged 85, and was buried alongside his wife Elvira Sima at [[Torredembarra]], near [[Barcelona]], Spain, although some sources cite his place of death as [[Augsburg]], Germany.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.bjt.ro/bv/ScritoriBanateni/VALENAS_Liviu/Valenasmiscarea.pdf|title=Mi\u015fcarea Legionari\u0103 - \u00centre Adev\u0103r \u015fi Mistificare|last=V\u0103lena\u015f|first=Liviu|publisher=Editura Marineasa|year=2000|isbn=|location=Timi\u0219oara|pages=171|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''[http://miscarea.com/horia-sima-english.htm Europe at the crossroads: war or capitulation?]''; [[Munich]] Verlag \"Vestitori\", 1955\n* ''The Rumanian situation after 19 years of Communist slavery and policies of the western powers, 1944-1963; a declaration by the Rumanian Legionary Movement;'' [[Rio de Janeiro]]?, 1963?\n* ''[http://miscarea.com/horia-sima-english1.htm Hunger In Romania];'' 1964\n* ''Articole politice, 1950-1963''; 1967\n* ''XLth anniversary of the foundation of the Rumanian legionary movement, 1927-1967; declarations of the legionary movement concerning the fate of the free world and the tragedy of the Rumanian people''; 1968\n* ''Ce este comunismul?''; Madrid, Editura Dacia, 1972\n* ''Histoire du Mouvement L\u00e9gionnaire''; Rio de Janeiro, 1972 (''The History of the Legionary Movement'', Legionary Press, 1995)\n* ''An interview with Horia Sima, Commander-in-chief, Legion of the Archangel Michael''; \"Thule of Palermo\", 1977\n* ''The Truth About The Legionary Movement''\n* ''The Natural World Order''\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*''Romanian Nationalism: The Legionary Movement'' by Alexander E. Ronnett  {{ISBN|0-8294-0232-2}} Chicago: Loyola University Press, 1995.\n*''The Green Shirts and the Others: A History of Fascism in Hungary and Rumania'' by [[Nicholas M. Nagy-Talavera]], 1970 {{ISBN|973-9432-11-5}} & {{ISBN|0-8179-1851-5}}\n*''[[Biographical Dictionary of the Extreme Right Since 1890]]'' edited by [[Philip Rees]], 1991, {{ISBN|0-13-089301-3}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020620015619/http://hist.academic.claremontmckenna.edu/jpetropoulos/ironguard/leaders.htm Leadership of the Iron Guard]\n* [http://www.axishistory.com/index.php?id=2353 Romanian volunteers in the Waffen-SS] by Marc Rikmenspoel\n\n*{{PM20|FID=pe/016573}}\n{{Gigurtu Cabinet}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sima, Horia}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219]]\n[[Category:Members of the Iron Guard]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Culture]]\n[[Category:World War II political leaders]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian collaborators with Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Romanian fascists]]\n[[Category:Romanian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Romanian Austro-Hungarians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Romanian Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Christian fascists]]\n[[Category:Holocaust perpetrators in Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian emigrants to Spain]]\n[[Category:People sentenced to death in absentia]]\n[[Category:Romanian prisoners sentenced to death]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to death by Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Romanian nationalists]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Romania]]\n[[Category:Anti-Masonry]]\n[[Category:Fascist rulers]]\n[[Category:Fascist politicians]]\n", "name_user": "RevAndroid", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed proper name of legionary movement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horia_Sima"}
{"title_page": "FIELDS", "text_new": "{{other uses|Fields (disambiguation){{!}}Fields}}\n[[File:Parker-Solar-Probe-FIELDS.png|thumb|350px|Overview of the FIELDS instrument on the ''Parker Solar Probe'']]\n[[File:Niobium crystals and 1cm3 cube.jpg|thumb|[[Niobium]] (shown here) is the main ingredient in the high-temperature C-103 alloy which the four whip antennas are made of, to endure direct exposure to the Sun at planned proximities]]\n[[File:A NASA Delta IV Heavy rocket launches the Parker Solar Probe (29097299447).jpg|thumb|FIELDS heads into space in August 2018 as part of the ''Parker Solar Probe'']]\n[[File:Amazing Hi-Def CME (6938834194).png|thumb|FIELDS is focused on increasing understanding of the Sun]]\n\n'''FIELDS''' is a science instrument on the ''[[Parker Solar Probe]]'' (PSP), designed to measure magnetic fields in the [[solar corona]] during its mission to study the Sun.{{r|ssr}} It is one of four major investigations on board PSP, along with WISPER, ISOIS, and SWEAP.{{r|ssr}} It features three [[Spacecraft magnetometer|magnetometer]]s.{{r|ssr}} FIELDS is planned to help answer an enduring questions about the Sun, such as why the solar corona is so hot compared to the surface of the Sun and why the solar wind is so fast (a million miles per hour).<ref name=\"CU Boulder Today\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.colorado.edu/today/2018/08/08/here-comes-sun-new-spacecraft-fly-closer-ever|title=Here comes the sun: New spacecraft to fly closer than ever before|date=2018-08-08|work=CU Boulder Today|access-date=2018-08-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe host spacecraft, ''[[Parker Solar Probe]]'', was launched by a [[Delta IV Heavy]] on August 12, 2018 from Florida, USA.<ref name=launch>{{Cite news|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=94|title=Parker Solar Probe Launches on Historic Journey to Touch the Sun|last=Brown|first=Geoffrey|date=August 12, 2018|work=Parker Solar Probe|access-date=August 13, 2018|last2=Brown|first2=Dwayne|language=en|last3=Fox|first3=Karen}}</ref> On August 13, 2018 FIELDS became the first instrument to be activated including beginning deployment of the 4 whip antenna (clamps unlocked) and extension of the magnetometer [[wikt:boom#Noun 2|boom]].<ref name=\":0\" /> On September 4, 2018 the whip antennas were deployed.<ref name=v3>{{Cite news|url=https://www.v3.co.uk/v3-uk/news/3062245/nasas-parker-solar-probe-brings-instruments-and-secondary-systems-online-ahead-of-schedule|title=NASA's Parker Solar Probe brings instruments and secondary systems online ahead of schedule {{!}} V3|work=V3|access-date=2018-09-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nFIELDS features three [[magnetometer]]s: two are [[Magnetometer#Fluxgate magnetometer|fluxgate magnetometers]], and the third is a [[search-coil magnetometer]].{{r|ssr}}  It has five voltage sensors, four of which extend beyond the spacecraft's [[heatshield]] and must directly endure the intense conditions at the planned distances of less than 9 solar radii to the Sun.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/parker-solar-probe-instruments |title=Parker Solar Probe Instruments |last=Garner |first=Rob |date=2018-07-12 |publisher=NASA |access-date=2018-08-17 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"PressKit\">{{cite web |title=NASA Press Kit: Parker Solar Probe |url=https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/parkersolarprobe_presskit_august2018_final.pdf |publisher=NASA |accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor best scientific observations, the spacecraft must approach to approximately about 10 [[Solar radius|solar radii]] (4% of the Earth-Sun distance) to take measurements from within the [[solar corona]].<ref name=\"eclipse2017.nso.edu\">[https://eclipse2017.nso.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/PSP_DKIST_CSP_v1.pdf eclipse2017.nso.edu]</ref> The task of FIELDS is to take measurements of the electrical and [[Solar dynamo|magnetic fields near the Sun]].<ref name=\"CU Boulder Today\"/> Most of FIELDS instrumentation is protected, along with the bulk of the spacecraft by a special 4.5 inch (11.43&nbsp;cm) thick carbon heatshield as the spacecraft is expected to endure temperatures of 2,500 degrees F.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2018/07/24/nasa-sun-probe-launch-date/ |title=NASA Probe That Will Touch Sun Set to Launch August 11| work=Fortune| access-date=2018-08-18 |language=en}}</ref> While the surface of the Sun is roughly 10,000 degrees F, the [[solar corona]] has a temperature exceeding 1 million\u00b0F.<ref name=\"CU Boulder Today\"/> (about half a million\u00b0C)\n\nPlanned measurements include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/Spacecraft/index.php|title=Parker Solar Probe: Spacecraft |last=JHUAPL |website=parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu |language=en |access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref>\n* electric and [[magnetic field]]s and waves\n* [[Alfven waves]] and turbulence<ref>[https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/p/psp directory.eoportal.org]</ref>\n* [[Poynting Flux|poynting flux]]\n* absolute [[Plasma (physics)|plasma density]] \n* [[electron temperature]]\n* spacecraft floating potential and density fluctuations\n* [[radio emission]]s\n\n==Components==\n\nThe key components of FIELDS are:<ref name=\"eclipse2017.nso.edu\"/>{{r|ssr}}\n*Five [[voltage]] sensors\n*Two [[fluxgate magnetometer]]s\n*One [[search-coil magnetometer]]\n*Main Electronics Package\n\nSupporting systems include four [[whip antenna]]s (called V1 through V4) that are 2 meters long and made of C-103 [[niobium alloy]].<ref name=ssr>{{Cite journal|last=Bale|first=S. D.|last2=Goetz|first2=K.|last3=Harvey|first3=P. R.|last4=Turin|first4=P.|last5=Bonnell|first5=J. W.|last6=Dudok de Wit|first6=T.|last7=Ergun|first7=R. E.|last8=MacDowall|first8=R. J.|last9=Pulupa|first9=M.|display-authors=etal|date=2016-03-31|title=The FIELDS Instrument Suite for Solar Probe Plus|journal=Space Science Reviews|language=en|volume=204|issue=1\u20134|pages=49\u201382|doi=10.1007/s11214-016-0244-5|issn=0038-6308|pmc=5942226|pmid=29755144|doi-access=free}}</ref> These antennas are numbered V1, V2, V3, and V4.{{r|ssr}} V5 is a voltage sensor on the end of the spacecraft's magnetometer boom. All five send signals to the ''Antenna Electronics Board'' which is part of the ''Main Electronics Package'', and each V1 to V5 has its own [[pre-amplifier]] that is sending this signal.{{r|ssr}} The sensors are integrated with various electrical and electronic processing systems which take in the raw signals and convert them into software data for transmission back to Earth by radio communication.{{r|ssr}}\n\nThe FIELDS experiment can also detect [[cosmic dust]], by recording the dust impact strikes on the antennas.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/sweap/about_spacecraft.html |title=The SWEAP Investigation for Parker Solar Probe |last=Kasper |first=Justin C. |website=www.cfa.harvard.edu |access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref> It will try to detect micron sized and nanodust, if carried by the solar wind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/p/psp|title=Parker Solar Probe - eoPortal Directory - Satellite Missions|website=directory.eoportal.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\"PSP/FIELDS Science \u2013 PSP/FIELDS\">{{Cite web | url=http://fields.ssl.berkeley.edu/science/ | title=PSP/FIELDS Science \u2013 PSP/FIELDS}}</ref> It detects and sizes dust impacts on its antennas by the voltage signature.<ref name=\"PSP/FIELDS Science \u2013 PSP/FIELDS\"/>\n\n==Operations==\nBy September 2018, FIELDS had been turned on and first data was returned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/2018/09/19/illuminating-first-light-data-from-parker-solar-probe/|title=Illuminating First Light Data from Parker Solar Probe \u2013 Parker Solar Probe|website=blogs.nasa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref> Data from FIELDS was designed for return from observations during the closer solar encounters of the ''Parker Solar Probe'' spacecraft in October\u2013November 2018 and March\u2013April 2019.<ref>[http://fields.ssl.berkeley.edu/]</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n*August 12, 2018; launched.\n*August 13, 2018; FIELDS instrument is powered on in outer space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.space.com/41531-parker-solar-probe-first-milestones-to-sun.html|title=NASA Solar Probe Hits 1st Deep-Space Milestones On Its Way to the Sun|work=Space.com|access-date=2018-08-18}}</ref>\n**The first activity conducted was opening the clamps that hold the antennas down during launch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/science/news/parker-solar-probe-operating-as-planned-nasa-says-1902537|title=Parker Solar Probe Operating as Planned, NASA Says|work=NDTV Gadgets360.com|access-date=2018-08-18|language=en}}</ref>\n**The next activity was to extend the magnetometer boom.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/2018/08/17/parker-solar-probe-marks-first-mission-milestones-on-voyage-to-sun/|title=Parker Solar Probe Marks First Mission Milestones on Voyage to Sun \u2013 Parker Solar Probe|website=blogs.nasa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-19}}</ref>\n*September 4, 2018 - four whip antennas deployed/extended.<ref name=v3 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/|title=Parker Solar Probe|website=blogs.nasa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Interior Characterization of Europa using Magnetometry]], a planned magnetometer for ''[[Europa Clipper]]''\n*[[Magnetometer (Juno)]], a magnetometer on board ''Juno'' Jupiter orbiter\n*[[Spacecraft magnetometer]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Psp}}\n{{Satellite and spacecraft instruments}}\n\n[[Category:Spacecraft instruments]]\n[[Category:Parker Solar Probe]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Fields (disambiguation){{!}}Fields}}\n[[File:Parker-Solar-Probe-FIELDS.png|thumb|350px|Overview of the FIELDS instrument on the ''Parker Solar Probe'']]\n[[File:Niobium crystals and 1cm3 cube.jpg|thumb|[[Niobium]] (shown here) is the main ingredient in the high-temperature C-103 alloy which the four whip antennas are made of, to endure direct exposure to the Sun at planned proximities]]\n[[File:A NASA Delta IV Heavy rocket launches the Parker Solar Probe (29097299447).jpg|thumb|FIELDS heads into space in August 2018 as part of the ''Parker Solar Probe'']]\n[[File:Amazing Hi-Def CME (6938834194).png|thumb|FIELDS is focused on increasing understanding of the Sun]]\n\n'''FIELDS''' is a science instrument on the ''[[Parker Solar Probe]]'' (PSP), designed to measure magnetic fields in the solar [[corona]] during its mission to study the Sun.{{r|ssr}} It is one of four major investigations on board PSP, along with WISPER, ISOIS, and SWEAP.{{r|ssr}} It features three [[Spacecraft magnetometer|magnetometer]]s.{{r|ssr}} FIELDS is planned to help answer an enduring questions about the Sun, such as why the solar corona is so hot compared to the surface of the Sun and why the solar wind is so fast (a million miles per hour).<ref name=\"CU Boulder Today\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.colorado.edu/today/2018/08/08/here-comes-sun-new-spacecraft-fly-closer-ever|title=Here comes the sun: New spacecraft to fly closer than ever before|date=2018-08-08|work=CU Boulder Today|access-date=2018-08-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe host spacecraft, ''[[Parker Solar Probe]]'', was launched by a [[Delta IV Heavy]] on August 12, 2018 from Florida, USA.<ref name=launch>{{Cite news|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=94|title=Parker Solar Probe Launches on Historic Journey to Touch the Sun|last=Brown|first=Geoffrey|date=August 12, 2018|work=Parker Solar Probe|access-date=August 13, 2018|last2=Brown|first2=Dwayne|language=en|last3=Fox|first3=Karen}}</ref> On August 13, 2018 FIELDS became the first instrument to be activated including beginning deployment of the 4 whip antenna (clamps unlocked) and extension of the magnetometer [[wikt:boom#Noun 2|boom]].<ref name=\":0\" /> On September 4, 2018 the whip antennas were deployed.<ref name=v3>{{Cite news|url=https://www.v3.co.uk/v3-uk/news/3062245/nasas-parker-solar-probe-brings-instruments-and-secondary-systems-online-ahead-of-schedule|title=NASA's Parker Solar Probe brings instruments and secondary systems online ahead of schedule {{!}} V3|work=V3|access-date=2018-09-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nFIELDS features three [[magnetometer]]s: two are [[Magnetometer#Fluxgate magnetometer|fluxgate magnetometers]], and the third is a [[search-coil magnetometer]].{{r|ssr}}  It has five voltage sensors, four of which extend beyond the spacecraft's [[heatshield]] and must directly endure the intense conditions at the planned distances of less than 9 solar radii to the Sun.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/parker-solar-probe-instruments |title=Parker Solar Probe Instruments |last=Garner |first=Rob |date=2018-07-12 |publisher=NASA |access-date=2018-08-17 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"PressKit\">{{cite web |title=NASA Press Kit: Parker Solar Probe |url=https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/parkersolarprobe_presskit_august2018_final.pdf |publisher=NASA |accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor best scientific observations, the spacecraft must approach to approximately about 10 [[Solar radius|solar radii]] (4% of the Earth-Sun distance) to take measurements from within the [[solar corona]].<ref name=\"eclipse2017.nso.edu\">[https://eclipse2017.nso.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/PSP_DKIST_CSP_v1.pdf eclipse2017.nso.edu]</ref> The task of FIELDS is to take measurements of the electrical and [[Solar dynamo|magnetic fields near the Sun]].<ref name=\"CU Boulder Today\"/> Most of FIELDS instrumentation is protected, along with the bulk of the spacecraft by a special 4.5 inch (11.43 cm) thick carbon heatshield as the spacecraft is expected to endure temperatures of 2,500 degrees F.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2018/07/24/nasa-sun-probe-launch-date/ |title=NASA Probe That Will Touch Sun Set to Launch August 11| work=Fortune| access-date=2018-08-18 |language=en}}</ref> While the surface of the Sun is roughly 10,000 degrees F, the [[solar corona]] has a temperature exceeding 1 million\u00b0F.<ref name=\"CU Boulder Today\"/> (about half a million\u00b0C)\n\nPlanned measurements include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/Spacecraft/index.php|title=Parker Solar Probe: Spacecraft |last=JHUAPL |website=parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu |language=en |access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref>\n* electric and [[magnetic field]]s and waves\n* [[Alfven waves]] and turbulence<reF>[https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/p/psp directory.eoportal.org]</ref>\n* [[Poynting Flux|poynting flux]]\n* absolute [[Plasma (physics)|plasma density]] \n* [[electron temperature]]\n* spacecraft floating potential and density fluctuations\n* [[radio emission]]s\n\n==Components==\n\nThe key components of FIELDS are:<ref name=\"eclipse2017.nso.edu\"/>{{r|ssr}}\n*Five [[voltage]] sensors\n*Two [[fluxgate magnetometer]]s\n*One [[search-coil magnetometer]]\n*Main Electronics Package\n\nSupporting systems include four [[whip antenna]]s (called V1 through V4) that are 2 meters long and made of C-103 [[niobium alloy]].<ref name=ssr>{{Cite journal|last=Bale|first=S. D.|last2=Goetz|first2=K.|last3=Harvey|first3=P. R.|last4=Turin|first4=P.|last5=Bonnell|first5=J. W.|last6=Dudok de Wit|first6=T.|last7=Ergun|first7=R. E.|last8=MacDowall|first8=R. J.|last9=Pulupa|first9=M.|display-authors=etal|date=2016-03-31|title=The FIELDS Instrument Suite for Solar Probe Plus|journal=Space Science Reviews|language=en|volume=204|issue=1\u20134|pages=49\u201382|doi=10.1007/s11214-016-0244-5|issn=0038-6308|pmc=5942226|pmid=29755144|doi-access=free}}</ref> These antennas are numbered V1, V2, V3, and V4.{{r|ssr}} V5 is a voltage sensor on the end of the spacecraft's magnetometer boom. All five send signals to the ''Antenna Electronics Board'' which is part of the ''Main Electronics Package'', and each V1 to V5 has its own [[pre-amplifier]] that is sending this signal.{{r|ssr}} The sensors are integrated with various electrical and electronic processing systems which take in the raw signals and convert them into software data for transmission back to Earth by radio communication.{{r|ssr}}\n\nThe FIELDS experiment can also detect [[cosmic dust]], by recording the dust impact strikes on the antennas.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/sweap/about_spacecraft.html |title=The SWEAP Investigation for Parker Solar Probe |last=Kasper |first=Justin C. |website=www.cfa.harvard.edu |access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref> It will try to detect micron sized and nanodust, if carried by the solar wind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://directory.eoportal.org/web/eoportal/satellite-missions/p/psp|title=Parker Solar Probe - eoPortal Directory - Satellite Missions|website=directory.eoportal.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-10}}</ref><reF>{{Cite web | url=http://fields.ssl.berkeley.edu/science/ | title=PSP/FIELDS Science \u2013 PSP/FIELDS}}</reF> It detects and sizes dust impacts on its antennas by the voltage signature.<reF>{{Cite web | url=http://fields.ssl.berkeley.edu/science/ | title=PSP/FIELDS Science \u2013 PSP/FIELDS}}</reF>\n\n==Operations==\nBy September 2018, FIELDS had been turned on and first data was returned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/2018/09/19/illuminating-first-light-data-from-parker-solar-probe/|title=Illuminating First Light Data from Parker Solar Probe \u2013 Parker Solar Probe|website=blogs.nasa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref> Data from FIELDS was designed for return from observations during the closer solar encounters of the ''Parker Solar Probe'' spacecraft in October-November 2018 and March-April 2019.<reF>[http://fields.ssl.berkeley.edu/]</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n*August 12, 2018; launched.\n*August 13, 2018; FIELDS instrument is powered on in outer space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.space.com/41531-parker-solar-probe-first-milestones-to-sun.html|title=NASA Solar Probe Hits 1st Deep-Space Milestones On Its Way to the Sun|work=Space.com|access-date=2018-08-18}}</ref>\n**The first activity conducted was opening the clamps that hold the antennas down during launch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/science/news/parker-solar-probe-operating-as-planned-nasa-says-1902537|title=Parker Solar Probe Operating as Planned, NASA Says|work=NDTV Gadgets360.com|access-date=2018-08-18|language=en}}</ref>\n**The next activity was to extend the magnetometer boom.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/2018/08/17/parker-solar-probe-marks-first-mission-milestones-on-voyage-to-sun/|title=Parker Solar Probe Marks First Mission Milestones on Voyage to Sun \u2013 Parker Solar Probe|website=blogs.nasa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-19}}</ref>\n*September 4, 2018 - four whip antennas deployed/extended.<ref name=v3 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/parkersolarprobe/|title=Parker Solar Probe|website=blogs.nasa.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Interior Characterization of Europa using Magnetometry]], a planned magnetometer for ''[[Europa Clipper]]''\n*[[Magnetometer (Juno)]], a magnetometer on board ''Juno'' Jupiter orbiter\n*[[Spacecraft magnetometer]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Psp}}\n{{Satellite and spacecraft instruments}}\n\n[[Category:Spacecraft instruments]]\n[[Category:Parker Solar Probe]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIELDS"}
